1
00:00:04,238 --> 00:00:05,306
(WOMAN GROANS)

2
00:00:06,207 --> 00:00:07,408
I can't...

3
00:00:12,513 --> 00:00:13,647
Nanine!

4
00:00:13,681 --> 00:00:15,183
Nanine!

5
00:00:15,216 --> 00:00:16,617
Nanine, 
 get the doctor quickly!

6
00:00:17,718 --> 00:00:20,221
(WEAKLY) Doctor?

7
00:00:20,254 --> 00:00:23,191
If you can't make me live, 
 how can he?

8
00:00:23,224 --> 00:00:25,459
No, no, don't say 
 such things, Marguerite.

9
00:00:25,493 --> 00:00:26,427
You'll live.

10
00:00:26,460 --> 00:00:28,696
You must live.

11
00:00:28,729 --> 00:00:31,099
MARGUERITE:
 Perhaps it's better 
 if I live in your heart...

12
00:00:31,132 --> 00:00:32,666
(WOMAN SNIFFLING)

13
00:00:32,700 --> 00:00:34,802
...where the world 
 can't see me.

14
00:00:34,835 --> 00:00:36,237
(SOBS SOFTLY)

15
00:00:36,270 --> 00:00:38,206
If I'm dead,

16
00:00:38,239 --> 00:00:40,408
there'll be no stain 
 on our love.

17
00:00:40,441 --> 00:00:41,775
Shh.

18
00:00:41,809 --> 00:00:44,412
Don't think such things, 
 Marguerite.

19
00:00:44,445 --> 00:00:47,248
Even if we've can't to go 
 to the country today,

20
00:00:47,281 --> 00:00:49,117
think of how happy 
 we were once,

21
00:00:49,150 --> 00:00:51,719
how happy 
 we shall be again.

22
00:00:51,752 --> 00:00:53,821
Think of the day you found 
 the four-leaf clover,

23
00:00:53,854 --> 00:00:56,490
of all the good luck 
 it's going to bring us.

24
00:00:56,524 --> 00:00:59,160
Think of the vows we heard 
 Nisha and Gustav make,

25
00:00:59,193 --> 00:01:02,296
and that we're going 
 to make to each other.

26
00:01:02,330 --> 00:01:04,064
This is for life, 
 Marguerite.

27
00:01:07,535 --> 00:01:08,536
Marguerite?

28
00:01:09,470 --> 00:01:10,704
(WHIMPERING)

29
00:01:11,872 --> 00:01:13,541
(SOBBING)

30
00:01:14,508 --> 00:01:15,776
Marguerite.

31
00:01:19,213 --> 00:01:21,182
Ah, don't leave me!

32
00:01:21,215 --> 00:01:22,816
(CRYING)
 Marguerite, come back! 
 Come back!

33
00:01:28,789 --> 00:01:30,291
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

34
00:01:30,324 --> 00:01:31,392
(WOMAN SNIFFLING)

35
00:01:45,273 --> 00:01:46,307
Jean?

36
00:02:07,361 --> 00:02:08,162
JEAN: Wow!

37
00:02:09,963 --> 00:02:11,465
SUSAN: It's just a movie.

38
00:02:11,499 --> 00:02:12,900
JEAN: Don't say that!

39
00:02:12,933 --> 00:02:14,502
When that last scene
was over,

40
00:02:14,535 --> 00:02:16,737
Garbo got up,
marched off
and went out to eat.

41
00:02:16,770 --> 00:02:17,838
JEAN: She died!

42
00:02:17,871 --> 00:02:20,274
She died
a few years ago.

43
00:02:20,308 --> 00:02:22,576
She died in
Robert Taylor's arms.

44
00:02:22,610 --> 00:02:24,478
-Oh, dear!
-Oh!

45
00:02:24,512 --> 00:02:26,280
If I'd known it was going
to affect you this way,

46
00:02:26,314 --> 00:02:28,449
I would've signed up
for the series with Fred.

47
00:02:28,482 --> 00:02:31,319
Of course,
he always falls asleep
before the end.

48
00:02:31,352 --> 00:02:33,554
He's seen
 Breakfast at Tiffany's 
a dozen times,

49
00:02:33,587 --> 00:02:36,257
he hasn't made it
to Moon River yet.

50
00:02:36,290 --> 00:02:37,891
How are things
between you and Fred?

51
00:02:41,595 --> 00:02:43,264
Wanna go for coffee?

52
00:02:44,565 --> 00:02:45,699
If we make it fast.

53
00:02:45,733 --> 00:02:48,836
I'm supposed
to be home by 11:00,
or Fred'll just have...

54
00:02:48,869 --> 00:02:50,338
We'll make it fast.

55
00:02:50,371 --> 00:02:51,939
-So tell me...
-Don't worry.

56
00:02:55,276 --> 00:02:57,611
Fred has you
on a curfew?

57
00:02:57,645 --> 00:02:59,547
He calls me at work
all hours of the day,

58
00:02:59,580 --> 00:03:00,981
he checks
on everything I do.

59
00:03:01,014 --> 00:03:03,351
(SOFTLY)
The affair was short,

60
00:03:03,384 --> 00:03:05,519
the repercussions
seem to be lasting forever.

61
00:03:06,854 --> 00:03:07,988
MAN: Can I get a latte?

62
00:03:08,021 --> 00:03:09,923
Are you going
to a therapist?

63
00:03:09,957 --> 00:03:11,825
SUSAN: When I tell Fred
where I've been
or what I've been doing,

64
00:03:11,859 --> 00:03:13,827
he thinks I'm lying.

65
00:03:13,861 --> 00:03:16,264
Now he's got this new thing,
when he gets home from work,
listen to this,

66
00:03:16,297 --> 00:03:17,931
he hits the redial button
on the phone

67
00:03:17,965 --> 00:03:19,433
to see who's the last person
I talked to.

68
00:03:19,467 --> 00:03:21,669
-No.
-The affair was pure sex.

69
00:03:21,702 --> 00:03:23,671
We didn't feel anything
for each other.

70
00:03:23,704 --> 00:03:25,839
We were polite
to each other.

71
00:03:25,873 --> 00:03:27,941
Well, I guess
sleeping with each other

72
00:03:27,975 --> 00:03:29,543
is the highest form
of politeness.

73
00:03:29,577 --> 00:03:30,544
(LAUGHS)

74
00:03:32,546 --> 00:03:34,982
It's not as if Fred and I
are doing anything.

75
00:03:37,818 --> 00:03:39,353
What are you staring at?

76
00:03:39,387 --> 00:03:40,288
Uh, no...

77
00:03:40,788 --> 00:03:41,855
Do you?

78
00:03:42,456 --> 00:03:43,691
Do I what?

79
00:03:43,724 --> 00:03:44,892
Do you and Roger
sleep together?

80
00:03:45,459 --> 00:03:46,527
Mmm-hmm.

81
00:03:46,560 --> 00:03:47,828
Yeah, I know you share
the same bed,

82
00:03:47,861 --> 00:03:49,029
Fred and I share
the same bed.

83
00:03:49,062 --> 00:03:51,432
I mean, do you and Roger
do anything in bed?

84
00:03:51,465 --> 00:03:52,466
Mmm-hmm.

85
00:03:53,667 --> 00:03:55,636
-After how many years?
-Fourteen.

86
00:03:58,306 --> 00:03:59,673
Guinness Book of Records 
 know about this?

87
00:04:02,510 --> 00:04:03,444
Not often, right?

88
00:04:04,011 --> 00:04:04,945
Fairly often.

89
00:04:06,914 --> 00:04:10,851
SUSAN: Well, often means
different things
to different people.

90
00:04:13,487 --> 00:04:15,556
-You know that man?
-JEAN: No.

91
00:04:15,589 --> 00:04:16,924
SUSAN: Youch!

92
00:04:16,957 --> 00:04:18,459
Wasn't he
at the movies?

93
00:04:18,492 --> 00:04:19,560
-(CUP CLATTERS)
-Uh-huh.

94
00:04:20,861 --> 00:04:22,530
Did you see
how he looked at you?

95
00:04:22,563 --> 00:04:23,797
Oh, stop it!

96
00:04:23,831 --> 00:04:25,899
-We got to get you home.
-(GASPS) Fred.

97
00:04:28,569 --> 00:04:30,504
(GIGGLING)

98
00:04:30,538 --> 00:04:32,706
It'd be so much more fun
if we drove home together.

99
00:04:32,740 --> 00:04:34,608
I wish,
but you know my hours,

100
00:04:34,642 --> 00:04:36,477
the only way I can get
anywhere near on time

101
00:04:36,510 --> 00:04:38,312
is if I leave
right from work.

102
00:04:38,346 --> 00:04:40,914
Oh, well,
whoever said that
office management was easy

103
00:04:40,948 --> 00:04:42,450
or highly paid...

104
00:04:42,483 --> 00:04:43,717
Well, I'll talk
to you tomorrow

105
00:04:43,751 --> 00:04:45,453
and I'll see you
next Monday.

106
00:04:45,486 --> 00:04:46,987
Oh, that's just
what I need.

107
00:04:47,020 --> 00:04:48,489
Vivien Leigh
in Anna Karenina,

108
00:04:48,522 --> 00:04:51,792
something to remind me
what happens to married women
who have affairs.

109
00:04:51,825 --> 00:04:53,661
Oh, no!

110
00:04:53,694 --> 00:04:55,529
Thank God
there are no trains
out where I live.

111
00:04:55,563 --> 00:04:56,830
(SUSAN LAUGHING)

112
00:04:59,867 --> 00:05:01,101
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

113
00:05:01,134 --> 00:05:02,870
JEAN: (SINGSONG) Morning!
ROGER: Hey!

114
00:05:03,937 --> 00:05:05,706
-I cooked.
-Thank you.

115
00:05:05,739 --> 00:05:07,074
Can I get you to do it
for me every day?

116
00:05:07,107 --> 00:05:08,709
Yeah, if you play
your cards right.

117
00:05:11,979 --> 00:05:14,382
Bess, could you please
turn off the sprinklers?

118
00:05:14,415 --> 00:05:16,584
Why don't you
put them on a timer?

119
00:05:16,617 --> 00:05:18,986
Well, I like to do it myself.
I feel like I'm part
of the earth.

120
00:05:19,019 --> 00:05:20,821
Well, I don't care to be
part of the earth.

121
00:05:20,854 --> 00:05:22,523
Just finish your breakfast,
please.

122
00:05:22,556 --> 00:05:23,391
I'm finished.

123
00:05:23,424 --> 00:05:24,825
Bess?

124
00:05:24,858 --> 00:05:26,126
I'll untie it
when I get to school.

125
00:05:26,159 --> 00:05:28,362
I think you should
untie it now.

126
00:05:28,396 --> 00:05:29,463
Mom!

127
00:05:29,497 --> 00:05:30,764
(MIMIC BESS) Mom!

128
00:05:30,798 --> 00:05:32,833
Hey, who wants more, huh?

129
00:05:32,866 --> 00:05:34,902
-No, thanks.
-What...

130
00:05:34,935 --> 00:05:36,336
No compliments
for the chef?

131
00:05:36,904 --> 00:05:37,938
(CAR ENGINE STARTING)

132
00:05:40,508 --> 00:05:41,409
(SHOUTS) Hey!

133
00:05:43,777 --> 00:05:46,780
I've got two stops to make
so I'll see you
in a half hour.

134
00:05:46,814 --> 00:05:48,582
I turn away for one minute.

135
00:05:48,616 --> 00:05:49,917
BOTH: Mom!

136
00:05:50,451 --> 00:05:51,752
JEAN: Bye!

137
00:05:56,089 --> 00:05:57,124
(SIGHS CONTENTLY)

138
00:05:57,925 --> 00:05:58,859
Ooh!

139
00:06:01,429 --> 00:06:02,095
Hips.

140
00:06:03,864 --> 00:06:04,865
Hips.

141
00:06:06,033 --> 00:06:06,900
Hips.

142
00:06:07,901 --> 00:06:08,902
(SOFTLY) Yeah.

143
00:06:10,471 --> 00:06:11,405
Hips, hips, hips.

144
00:06:12,973 --> 00:06:14,842
Excuse me?

145
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:16,777
Could you have
a look at this, please?

146
00:06:16,810 --> 00:06:19,046
Ah, you need to see
my wife for this.

147
00:06:20,047 --> 00:06:21,849
-Jean?
-JEAN: Yeah?

148
00:06:24,685 --> 00:06:26,186
Have a problem.

149
00:06:26,219 --> 00:06:28,055
Well, let's take a look at it.

150
00:06:28,088 --> 00:06:29,990
My roses, they get
all set to open up,

151
00:06:30,023 --> 00:06:31,692
then they collapse
and go brown.

152
00:06:31,725 --> 00:06:33,093
Hmm. Thrips.

153
00:06:34,194 --> 00:06:35,463
You need to use a systemic.

154
00:06:37,598 --> 00:06:39,633
White lightning.

155
00:06:39,667 --> 00:06:42,135
I never understood
why it didn't get the rating
it deserved.

156
00:06:42,169 --> 00:06:44,204
Well, I'll just buy
a new one.

157
00:06:44,237 --> 00:06:46,774
Oh, no, it's really easy
to get rid of this.

158
00:06:46,807 --> 00:06:48,041
If you can save a child,
you should.

159
00:06:48,842 --> 00:06:49,943
It's a rose.

160
00:06:49,977 --> 00:06:51,779
To me, they're like children.

161
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:53,881
In some ways they are.

162
00:06:55,516 --> 00:06:57,451
(PHONE RINGING)

163
00:06:57,485 --> 00:06:59,787
ROGER: Hello?
Well, yeah. Just a second.

164
00:06:59,820 --> 00:07:01,989
Jean, it's for you.

165
00:07:02,022 --> 00:07:03,023
Susan!

166
00:07:03,857 --> 00:07:05,192
Got it!

167
00:07:05,225 --> 00:07:06,927
Hello.

168
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:08,061
(JEAN HUMMING SOFTLY)

169
00:07:12,666 --> 00:07:13,901
You want to go
to the movies?

170
00:07:15,903 --> 00:07:18,639
Oh, I got to do this.

171
00:07:18,672 --> 00:07:21,575
Fred and Susan have
another emergency session
with their shrink.

172
00:07:21,609 --> 00:07:23,477
They're still going
to that shrink?

173
00:07:23,511 --> 00:07:24,678
Yeah, what does that mean?

174
00:07:24,712 --> 00:07:26,680
What does it mean?

175
00:07:26,714 --> 00:07:30,183
Well, neither Susan or Fred
ever saw a shrink
before they got married,

176
00:07:30,217 --> 00:07:32,586
so what I think it means is
maybe Susan and Fred

177
00:07:32,620 --> 00:07:33,921
don't bring out the best
in each other.

178
00:07:33,954 --> 00:07:35,022
Hmm.

179
00:07:35,055 --> 00:07:36,890
Ah, it happens.

180
00:07:36,924 --> 00:07:38,992
-What's the movie?
 -Anna Karenina.

181
00:07:39,292 --> 00:07:40,160
Who?

182
00:07:41,128 --> 00:07:42,029
Not for you.

183
00:07:42,062 --> 00:07:44,231
Ask me again
when they're showing, uh...

184
00:07:46,734 --> 00:07:48,602
BOTH: Clint Eastwood!

185
00:07:48,636 --> 00:07:49,537
Okay. Bye-bye.

186
00:07:49,570 --> 00:07:51,705
(BOTH LAUGH)

187
