(AUDIENCE EXCLAIMING)

207
00:09:15,055 --> 00:09:15,989
(JEAN SNIFFLING)

208
00:09:28,836 --> 00:09:30,871
It's wrinkled,
but it's clean.

209
00:09:32,139 --> 00:09:33,206
Thank you.

210
00:09:39,246 --> 00:09:42,149
Did you like Vivien Leigh
more than the Garbo version?

211
00:09:42,182 --> 00:09:45,152
Oh, Garbo,
she had those eyes.

212
00:09:45,185 --> 00:09:45,986
Yeah.

213
00:09:48,789 --> 00:09:50,323
I liked this one better.

214
00:09:52,860 --> 00:09:54,227
But you don't have to
ask me why.

215
00:10:01,134 --> 00:10:03,070
ATTENDANT: Thank you, ma'am.
Good night.

216
00:10:04,805 --> 00:10:06,239
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

217
00:10:20,854 --> 00:10:22,022
Excuse me.

218
00:10:23,390 --> 00:10:26,326
Uh, would you like
to have a cup of coffee?

219
00:10:26,359 --> 00:10:28,662
I mean, it's early.
We can talk about the movie.

220
00:10:28,696 --> 00:10:30,063
Thank you,
I don't think so.

221
00:10:31,164 --> 00:10:33,300
Ah, look, um,
I'm sorry.

222
00:10:34,434 --> 00:10:35,969
I'm not trying
to pick you up.

223
00:10:38,138 --> 00:10:39,439
My name is Tom Doster,

224
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:42,642
I'm a 40-something,
I'm married, happily,
I might add and...

225
00:10:44,211 --> 00:10:46,213
Well, I'm the father
of a terrific son.

226
00:10:46,246 --> 00:10:48,749
I know all fathers say
that their sons are terrific,

227
00:10:48,782 --> 00:10:49,917
but mine really is.

228
00:10:52,085 --> 00:10:54,087
Well,
I'm a structural engineer.

229
00:10:54,121 --> 00:10:56,389
I could go into great detail
about what that involves,

230
00:10:56,423 --> 00:11:00,227
but to keep it simple,
I just tell people
I build things.

231
00:11:00,260 --> 00:11:03,363
My wife was going to come
with me to this film series,

232
00:11:03,396 --> 00:11:05,733
but Mondays aren't
a good night for her

233
00:11:05,766 --> 00:11:08,235
because she volunteers
for project Helping Hand,

234
00:11:08,268 --> 00:11:11,138
and they cook things
for people who can't
cook for themselves.

235
00:11:13,974 --> 00:11:15,275
You sold me.

236
00:11:16,309 --> 00:11:17,945
Good.

237
00:11:17,978 --> 00:11:19,947
I'm sorry, I didn't even
tell you my name.

238
00:11:19,980 --> 00:11:21,448
My name is Jean,
Jean Townsend.

239
00:11:21,481 --> 00:11:22,816
-Jean.
-Hi.

240
00:11:23,450 --> 00:11:25,853
Um, you were born here?

241
00:11:26,854 --> 00:11:28,956
-Colorado.
-Ah, Colorado.

242
00:11:28,989 --> 00:11:31,258
And you've lived here,
say, ten years.

243
00:11:31,291 --> 00:11:33,794
See, I have these incredible
psychic powers.

244
00:11:33,827 --> 00:11:34,895
Seven.

245
00:11:35,395 --> 00:11:37,064
-Seven.
-Hmm.

246
00:11:37,097 --> 00:11:39,967
Now, you're married
and no children?

247
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:41,835
Married and one daughter.

248
00:11:41,869 --> 00:11:43,303
See, I used to be
a lot better at this.

249
00:11:43,336 --> 00:11:44,471
(JEAN LAUGHS)

250
00:11:45,839 --> 00:11:48,976
So, uh, you're a nurse?

251
00:11:49,309 --> 00:11:50,377
Close.

252
00:11:50,410 --> 00:11:51,979
I own a nursery.

253
00:11:52,012 --> 00:11:54,181
Ah, lots of little
children running around?

254
00:11:54,214 --> 00:11:56,449
No, it's not that kind
of a nursery.

255
00:11:56,483 --> 00:11:58,886
Well, Climbing Rose nursery
in Topanga.

256
00:11:58,919 --> 00:12:00,220
We got a lot of little
bushes running around.

257
00:12:02,890 --> 00:12:05,425
-So, you own a nursery.
-Mmm-hmm.

258
00:12:05,458 --> 00:12:08,261
My parents lent
Roger and I the money

259
00:12:08,295 --> 00:12:10,764
and we wanted to
pay them back in five years,
we paid them back in three.

260
00:12:10,798 --> 00:12:11,899
I'm very proud of that.

261
00:12:12,432 --> 00:12:13,433
That's great!

262
00:12:15,202 --> 00:12:19,973
So, um, why do you think
people go to see
these old movies?

263
00:12:21,975 --> 00:12:26,246
Well, there's not much
romance and passion today.

264
00:12:26,279 --> 00:12:27,815
I think people need it.

265
00:12:27,848 --> 00:12:29,182
The old movies
are a way to get it.

266
00:12:29,950 --> 00:12:31,819
Really?

267
00:12:31,852 --> 00:12:34,087
Even the man of the '90s
needs romance?

268
00:12:34,121 --> 00:12:36,123
Especially a man of the '90s.

269
00:12:36,824 --> 00:12:37,958
Hmm.

270
00:12:37,991 --> 00:12:40,961
Here I thought women
had the market cornered
on romance.

271
00:12:42,295 --> 00:12:43,296
No way.

272
00:12:49,903 --> 00:12:51,038
JEAN: Thank you.

273
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:54,908
I'm over there.

274
00:12:54,942 --> 00:12:57,010
You don't have
to walk with me.

275
00:12:57,044 --> 00:12:58,846
-See you next week.
-Yes.

276
00:12:58,879 --> 00:13:00,080
My friend Susan
will be back by then.

277
00:13:01,314 --> 00:13:03,183
Ah, what is the film
next week?

278
00:13:03,216 --> 00:13:05,352
Betty Davis, Now Voyager.

279
00:13:05,385 --> 00:13:07,420
Oh, my, double hanky.

280
00:13:07,454 --> 00:13:08,521
Cloth hanky.

281
00:13:15,495 --> 00:13:16,830
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

282
00:13:23,636 --> 00:13:26,306
-How was the movie?
-I cried my eyes out.

283
00:13:26,339 --> 00:13:28,141
Hmm, must've been good.

284
00:13:32,112 --> 00:13:34,081
Funniest thing
happened to me tonight.

285
00:13:34,114 --> 00:13:35,115
Hmm.

286
00:13:36,549 --> 00:13:39,186
Roger, are you awake?

287
00:13:39,219 --> 00:13:41,488
The funniest thing happened
to you tonight.

288
00:13:41,521 --> 00:13:43,590
Mmm-hmm.

289
00:13:43,623 --> 00:13:47,895
This really nice man
that I was sitting next to
asked me out for coffee.

290
00:13:52,432 --> 00:13:54,034
Roger?

291
00:13:54,067 --> 00:13:56,236
Ah, this really nice man
asked you out for coffee.

292
00:13:57,905 --> 00:13:59,339
I don't think that's unusual,

293
00:13:59,372 --> 00:14:02,009
if I saw you alone,
I'd ask you for coffee, too.

294
00:14:09,316 --> 00:14:12,185
Oh, I forgot to put
the coffee on for tomorrow.

295
00:14:12,219 --> 00:14:14,321
I knew you'd be late.
I did it.

296
00:14:15,989 --> 00:14:18,158
Ah, I'm so domestic
in my old age.

297
00:14:21,294 --> 00:14:23,363
You're still looking
pretty good,

298
00:14:23,396 --> 00:14:24,898
for an old man.

299
00:14:45,452 --> 00:14:46,954
Hey, Dad!

300
00:14:56,229 --> 00:14:57,230
(BARKS)

301
00:15:05,238 --> 00:15:06,673
Hey! How was the water?

302
00:15:06,706 --> 00:15:07,941
-It was great.
-Good!

303
00:15:07,975 --> 00:15:10,110
And, I was
damn good today, too.

304
00:15:10,143 --> 00:15:13,046
When did you start using
words like that?

305
00:15:13,080 --> 00:15:15,482
Want to hear the words
I don't use around you?

306
00:15:15,515 --> 00:15:17,450
No. Ask me again in ten years.

307
00:15:24,724 --> 00:15:27,327
KEVIN: How come
you're turning here?
This isn't the right way home.

308
00:15:27,360 --> 00:15:30,063
TOM: Well, I thought you might
enjoy the scenic route.

309
00:15:30,097 --> 00:15:32,432
KEVIN: Come on, Dad,
I've got things to do.

310
00:15:32,465 --> 00:15:34,401
TOM: This will be pretty,
trust me.

311
00:15:34,434 --> 00:15:36,336
KEVIN: I'm twelve,
what choice do I have?

312
00:16:32,659 --> 00:16:33,660
(INAUDIBLE)

313
00:16:35,762 --> 00:16:36,763
(HONKS)

314
00:16:40,267 --> 00:16:41,068
Dad?

315
00:16:59,486 --> 00:17:01,521
Excuse me?
The Anniversary section.

316
00:17:01,554 --> 00:17:03,456
-Oh, just around the corner.
-Thank you.

317
00:17:05,358 --> 00:17:06,626
ATTENDANT: You want a basket
for all of that?

318
00:17:06,659 --> 00:17:08,761
TOM: Well, I think I've got
everything I need.

319
00:17:08,795 --> 00:17:11,698
Oh, I forgot candles,
that's the most
important thing, right?

320
00:17:11,731 --> 00:17:13,500
ATTENDANT: Two aisles over.
TOM: Thank you.

321
00:17:15,435 --> 00:17:17,137
Well, small world!

322
00:17:19,306 --> 00:17:21,474
-What are you doing here?
-(CHUCKLES)

323
00:17:21,508 --> 00:17:24,277
It's my parents'
50th wedding anniversary
this coming week,

324
00:17:24,311 --> 00:17:25,812
and they're coming in
from Denver.

325
00:17:25,845 --> 00:17:27,247
I thought I'd throw them
a little party at home.

326
00:17:29,282 --> 00:17:31,818
I saw you the other day,
when you drove by?

327
00:17:33,120 --> 00:17:34,421
Why didn't you come in?

328
00:17:34,454 --> 00:17:37,124
Well, I didn't really
think about it.

329
00:17:37,157 --> 00:17:39,092
I would have given you
the grand tour.

330
00:17:39,126 --> 00:17:41,394
Oh, my son was with me.

331
00:17:41,428 --> 00:17:43,230
Well! You could've
brought him in.

332
00:17:43,263 --> 00:17:44,164
It's just a nursery.

333
00:17:44,631 --> 00:17:46,199
Yeah.

334
00:17:46,233 --> 00:17:48,835
My secretary's birthday,
surprising her.

335
00:17:48,868 --> 00:17:51,070
Having lunch brought in,
you know.

336
00:17:51,871 --> 00:17:54,207
Boss and his secretary.

337
00:17:54,241 --> 00:17:55,608
Have you really
thought about that?

338
00:17:55,642 --> 00:17:56,776
The boss and his secretary,

339
00:17:56,809 --> 00:17:59,612
or you know,
boss and her secretary?

340
00:17:59,646 --> 00:18:01,614
It's like they almost
have a marriage,

341
00:18:01,648 --> 00:18:04,817
they spend the same
amount of time together
as a husband and wife.

342
00:18:06,453 --> 00:18:07,454
Hmm, what color?

343
00:18:08,588 --> 00:18:09,756
I don't know.

344
00:18:12,159 --> 00:18:14,361
Margaret's a pink person.

345
00:18:14,394 --> 00:18:16,196
How many of these in a box?

346
00:18:16,229 --> 00:18:18,398
ATTENDANT: Uh, fifty.

347
00:18:18,431 --> 00:18:20,600
Need another one,
Margaret's 63,
you know.

348
00:18:23,670 --> 00:18:26,206
ATTENDANT:
So, is that everything? Good.

349
00:18:27,640 --> 00:18:28,808
GIRL: Jennifer...

350
00:18:30,910 --> 00:18:32,612
So?

351
00:18:32,645 --> 00:18:34,347
Would you like
to get some lunch?

352
00:18:34,381 --> 00:18:36,216
-Oh, well, I...
-I mean, what the hell!

353
00:18:36,249 --> 00:18:38,285
Come on,
we both got to eat, right?

354
00:18:38,318 --> 00:18:40,653
Yeah. Okay, all right.

355
00:18:45,192 --> 00:18:47,760
And I wanted to give
my parents a big, fancy party

356
00:18:47,794 --> 00:18:49,696
cause 50 years is 50 years.

357
00:18:49,729 --> 00:18:51,864
My mother wouldn't have it.

358
00:18:51,898 --> 00:18:55,602
Now, she said that
a golden wedding anniversary
only celebrates good luck,

359
00:18:55,635 --> 00:18:58,905
luck that you didn't die
before you got there.
(LAUGHING)

360
00:18:58,938 --> 00:19:00,773
My mom is very,
very practical.

361
00:19:00,807 --> 00:19:02,342
Yeah.

362
00:19:02,375 --> 00:19:04,211
How about a big,
gooey piece of cake?

363
00:19:04,244 --> 00:19:06,646
-Oh, no way!
-Oh, come on, two forks?

364
00:19:06,679 --> 00:19:09,182
No, no.
What are you working on?

365
00:19:09,216 --> 00:19:10,917
What's the engineer
engineering?

366
00:19:10,950 --> 00:19:13,686
Well, it's a new
bank building,

367
00:19:13,720 --> 00:19:16,189
going to have it
framed soon.

368
00:19:16,223 --> 00:19:17,857
You are accusing it
of something it didn't do?

369
00:19:17,890 --> 00:19:19,058
Ah, no.

370
00:19:19,091 --> 00:19:22,362
That's when you get the last
piece of steel set in place.

371
00:19:22,395 --> 00:19:23,496
I know.

372
00:19:23,530 --> 00:19:25,898
I know,
it was a terrible joke,
but I couldn't resist.

373
00:19:28,335 --> 00:19:30,837
Still, it must be wonderful
when you look at a building
years from now

374
00:19:30,870 --> 00:19:32,905
and you know you put it there.

375
00:19:35,508 --> 00:19:37,910
Well, every engineer
would like to believe that.

376
00:19:39,979 --> 00:19:41,948
-Yeah, I'll get this.
-Oh, no, no, no, no.

377
00:19:41,981 --> 00:19:43,416
Oh, come on,
it's only 12 bucks.

378
00:19:43,450 --> 00:19:45,385
No, please.

379
00:19:45,418 --> 00:19:46,853
All right, you can get it.

380
00:19:46,886 --> 00:19:48,921
I think we should split it.

381
00:19:48,955 --> 00:19:50,923
I'm sorry,
it's the only way I'll do it.

382
00:19:56,929 --> 00:19:58,398
It's very nice
to see you again.

383
00:19:58,431 --> 00:20:00,367
Same here.

384
00:20:00,400 --> 00:20:02,001
Will you be
at the movies tonight?

385
00:20:02,034 --> 00:20:04,003
Sure as shootin'.

386
00:20:04,036 --> 00:20:06,606
Haven't said that since
I was a little boy in Texas.

387
00:20:06,639 --> 00:20:08,875
Maybe you're
still a little boy.

388
00:20:08,908 --> 00:20:11,311
I meant that
in the very nicest way.

389
00:20:11,344 --> 00:20:12,412
That's all right.

390
00:20:13,980 --> 00:20:16,749
Well, uh, I guess I'll go,
I'm going to be late.

391
00:20:18,017 --> 00:20:19,552
-See ya!
-Bye.

392
00:20:25,592 --> 00:20:26,726
(PHONE RINGING)

393
00:20:26,759 --> 00:20:28,361
I think maybe
the mashed potatoes
will be better.

394
00:20:28,395 --> 00:20:29,362
Yeah.

395
00:20:29,396 --> 00:20:30,997
-Oh, really?
-Think so.

396
00:20:31,030 --> 00:20:32,432
-Depends on how they taste.
-Excuse me.

397
00:20:32,465 --> 00:20:33,600
(BESS CHUCKLES)

398
00:20:33,633 --> 00:20:35,268
(RINGING CONTINUES)

399
00:20:35,302 --> 00:20:36,436
Yeah, just a second.

400
00:20:36,469 --> 00:20:37,670
Hello?

401
00:20:37,704 --> 00:20:38,938
SUSAN: Hello, honey.

402
00:20:38,971 --> 00:20:40,006
Hi, what's up?

403
00:20:40,039 --> 00:20:42,041
My fever, that's what.

404
00:20:42,074 --> 00:20:44,311
I didn't even go in today.

405
00:20:44,344 --> 00:20:46,045
I kept thinking this cold 
 would go away,

406
00:20:46,078 --> 00:20:47,480
but it hasn't.

407
00:20:48,748 --> 00:20:49,949
I'm not going out.

408
00:20:50,817 --> 00:20:53,620
Sure, sure, don't worry.

409
00:20:54,387 --> 00:20:55,522
Worry?

410
00:20:55,555 --> 00:20:57,424
I've just got a cold.

411
00:20:57,457 --> 00:20:58,958
Okay, all right, then.
Buh-bye.

412
00:21:03,696 --> 00:21:05,598
(ROGER CHATTING WITH BESS)

413
00:21:08,701 --> 00:21:09,769
ROGER: Who was that?

414
00:21:10,537 --> 00:21:11,904
-Susan.
-Hmm.

415
00:21:11,938 --> 00:21:13,540
Telling me not to be late.

416
00:21:14,507 --> 00:21:15,975
(BESS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

417
00:21:18,077 --> 00:21:19,579
BESS: You can shop.

418
00:21:19,612 --> 00:21:23,282
ROGER: Hmm, well, seems
like you've been doing
a lot of shopping lately.

419
00:21:37,129 --> 00:21:38,297
Whoa! Whoa! Whoa!

420
00:21:40,066 --> 00:21:41,401
Let me see.

421
00:21:44,804 --> 00:21:47,774
Well, don't you look
like a million bucks!

422
00:21:47,807 --> 00:21:49,476
Oh, stop. (LAUGHS)

423
00:21:55,782 --> 00:21:56,916
Jerry, please help me.

424
00:22:01,854 --> 00:22:03,623
Shall we just have 
 a cigarette on it?

425
00:22:05,758 --> 00:22:06,759
Yes.

426
00:22:19,472 --> 00:22:20,339
(LIGHTER CLICKS)

427
00:22:40,059 --> 00:22:41,027
(WHISPERING) When I was young,

428
00:22:41,060 --> 00:22:43,496
I didn't care to look
like Elizabeth Taylor,

429
00:22:43,530 --> 00:22:46,065
or have Rita Hayworth's body,
or Marlene Dietrich's legs,

430
00:22:46,098 --> 00:22:48,635
I wanted to smoke
like Betty Davis.

431
00:22:48,668 --> 00:22:50,537
Yeah, but you don't.

432
00:22:50,570 --> 00:22:51,671
No, it's bad for you.

433
00:22:59,979 --> 00:23:01,481
We could talk 
 about your child.

434
00:23:01,514 --> 00:23:02,815
Our child.

435
00:23:04,917 --> 00:23:05,918
Thank you.

436
00:23:07,554 --> 00:23:10,457
JERRY: And will you be happy, 
 Charlotte?

437
00:23:10,490 --> 00:23:13,192
Oh, Jerry, don't let's ask 
 for the moment.

438
00:23:13,225 --> 00:23:14,561
We have the stars.

439
00:23:32,712 --> 00:23:34,714
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

440
00:23:36,583 --> 00:23:37,450
(CAR HONKING)

441
00:23:39,786 --> 00:23:41,621
You know, it's still early,

442
00:23:41,654 --> 00:23:43,122
you sure you don't want
to change your mind

443
00:23:43,155 --> 00:23:44,791
about having that
cup of coffee?

444
00:23:44,824 --> 00:23:46,926
No, I have a busy day
tomorrow.

445
00:23:46,959 --> 00:23:48,160
I really should go.

446
00:23:48,194 --> 00:23:49,195
-All right.
-Okay.

447
00:24:14,120 --> 00:24:15,622
So?

448
00:24:15,655 --> 00:24:16,989
Anything I can do?

449
00:24:17,023 --> 00:24:19,158
Yeah, you can take out
the potatoes and drain 'em
and mash 'em.

450
00:24:19,191 --> 00:24:21,528
Oh, this looks heavy.

451
00:24:21,561 --> 00:24:22,929
I'll do it.

452
00:24:22,962 --> 00:24:23,963
Oh.

453
00:24:27,967 --> 00:24:30,102
Uh, why don't I
set the table?

454
00:24:30,136 --> 00:24:30,870
It's buffet.

455
00:24:32,905 --> 00:24:33,940
I offered to split
half the cost,

456
00:24:33,973 --> 00:24:36,543
I said, "Let's get a caterer,"
but you wouldn't.

457
00:24:36,576 --> 00:24:38,811
I'm not good
at this sort of thing
and I don't pretend to be.

458
00:24:39,912 --> 00:24:41,247
Why don't you
check on Dad's drink?

459
00:24:45,685 --> 00:24:47,987
My rich sister,
my rich widowed sister.

460
00:24:48,020 --> 00:24:50,222
It's hard to believe
you two are even related.

461
00:24:51,157 --> 00:24:52,925
I do like the jewelry, though.

462
00:24:52,959 --> 00:24:55,061
Mmm. It's all real, too,
of course.

463
00:24:55,094 --> 00:24:57,864
Ugh, she must have
more money than God.

464
00:24:57,897 --> 00:24:59,599
Some people have
all the luck.

465
00:24:59,632 --> 00:25:01,000
Ah, I don't know.

466
00:25:01,033 --> 00:25:02,735
Maybe Phillip had
all the luck, he died.

467
00:25:02,769 --> 00:25:04,537
-(CHUCKLES)
-I heard that.

468
00:25:04,571 --> 00:25:05,872
Daddy doesn't want
another drink,

469
00:25:05,905 --> 00:25:07,039
he only wants a soda.

470
00:25:07,907 --> 00:25:09,141
Coming right up!

471
00:25:14,013 --> 00:25:15,214
You got the ones
in the cans?

472
00:25:15,882 --> 00:25:17,617
Uh-huh.

473
00:25:17,650 --> 00:25:19,051
With the lift-up tabs?

474
00:25:19,085 --> 00:25:19,886
Yeah.

475
00:25:21,053 --> 00:25:22,054
Susan?

476
00:25:25,725 --> 00:25:26,759
Oh.

477
00:25:34,867 --> 00:25:36,068
(LAUGHS)

478
00:25:40,139 --> 00:25:43,042
Did Roger say anything
about last Monday night?

479
00:25:43,075 --> 00:25:44,611
Huh?

480
00:25:44,644 --> 00:25:46,846
Last Monday night,
did he ask you anything
about it?

481
00:25:47,714 --> 00:25:48,915
What was Monday night?

482
00:25:48,948 --> 00:25:49,949
Film series.

483
00:25:50,950 --> 00:25:51,984
I had a cold.

484
00:25:52,018 --> 00:25:54,020
I know you had a cold.

485
00:25:54,053 --> 00:25:55,021
Did he ask you
anything about it?

486
00:25:56,889 --> 00:25:57,990
What?

487
00:26:00,159 --> 00:26:01,260
WOMAN: That's butter...

488
00:26:01,293 --> 00:26:02,795
You can't eat that,
it's bad.

489
00:26:02,829 --> 00:26:04,030
Have some of that.

490
00:26:04,764 --> 00:26:06,565
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

491
00:26:08,701 --> 00:26:09,936
Can I get you a plate?

492
00:26:18,177 --> 00:26:20,880
I wish they would
all go home.

493
00:26:20,913 --> 00:26:22,214
(CHUCKLES)

494
00:26:22,248 --> 00:26:23,082
What's wrong?

495
00:26:24,917 --> 00:26:28,020
I never told Roger
that you weren't at
the movies last Monday.

496
00:26:28,054 --> 00:26:31,023
So when you came here today,
I thought he might
ask you something,

497
00:26:31,057 --> 00:26:32,925
uh, whether
you liked it or not,

498
00:26:32,959 --> 00:26:34,794
and you wouldn't know
any better than to answer.

499
00:26:34,827 --> 00:26:36,328
Why didn't you tell Roger
I wasn't going?

500
00:26:39,231 --> 00:26:40,032
Oh, I get it.

501
00:26:41,901 --> 00:26:43,135
That guy was there last week.

502
00:26:43,169 --> 00:26:44,837
You've been seeing
that guy at the movies.

503
00:26:44,871 --> 00:26:46,839
There's no guy at the movies.

504
00:26:46,873 --> 00:26:47,807
What am I supposed
to call him?

505
00:26:47,840 --> 00:26:48,941
His name is Tom.

506
00:26:49,876 --> 00:26:51,343
Don't worry.

507
00:26:51,377 --> 00:26:53,846
I'll cover for you
if Roger asks anything.

508
00:26:53,880 --> 00:26:55,147
There's nothing to cover!
Okay?

509
00:26:56,215 --> 00:26:57,283
There's nothing to cover.

510
00:26:57,316 --> 00:26:58,818
Then, why are you
so nervous?

511
00:26:58,851 --> 00:27:00,987
Why didn't you tell Roger
I was sick last week?

512
00:27:01,020 --> 00:27:04,156
Why didn't you tell Roger
I didn't go to the movies
last week?

513
00:27:13,465 --> 00:27:14,566
MAN:
We're going to take off.

514
00:27:14,600 --> 00:27:16,435
ROGER: Yeah, okay, Fred.
Good seeing you. Take care.

515
00:27:16,468 --> 00:27:17,937
FRED: Yeah, you, too.

516
00:27:22,408 --> 00:27:26,078
Oh, it is so peaceful here!

517
00:27:26,112 --> 00:27:27,914
-Can I get you anything?
-No.

518
00:27:29,215 --> 00:27:31,117
Oh, it's a lovely party, dear.

519
00:27:31,150 --> 00:27:33,052
Oh, I'm glad you enjoyed it.

520
00:27:33,085 --> 00:27:34,787
You know I appreciate it,
don't you?

521
00:27:34,821 --> 00:27:36,422
Mmm-hmm.

522
00:27:36,455 --> 00:27:40,092
Did Brooke help you out any?

523
00:27:40,126 --> 00:27:42,328
She wrote a check,
Roger tore it up.

524
00:27:42,361 --> 00:27:43,763
(BOTH LAUGHING)

525
00:27:43,796 --> 00:27:45,197
He shouldn't have.

526
00:27:47,800 --> 00:27:51,003
Oh, I love both my daughters.

527
00:27:51,037 --> 00:27:55,407
Brooke is all on the surface
and you're the deep one.

528
00:27:55,441 --> 00:27:58,144
How those things are decided,
I have no idea.

529
00:27:58,177 --> 00:28:00,747
Mother, have you ever...

530
00:28:02,481 --> 00:28:03,282
What, dear?

531
00:28:04,951 --> 00:28:08,154
Have you ever been attracted
to another man besides Daddy?

532
00:28:08,187 --> 00:28:10,222
(GASPS) What a question!

533
00:28:10,256 --> 00:28:12,725
On my golden
wedding anniversary!

534
00:28:12,759 --> 00:28:14,260
(LAUGHS) I'm sorry.

535
00:28:14,293 --> 00:28:18,765
Honestly, Jean, your timing
somehow confounds me.

536
00:28:19,766 --> 00:28:20,800
Have you?

537
00:28:22,134 --> 00:28:22,969
Nope.

538
00:28:24,971 --> 00:28:28,174
It was only your father
from the first day we met.

539
00:28:28,207 --> 00:28:31,377
Didn't you ever
look at another man
in a mall or...

540
00:28:32,845 --> 00:28:35,081
A movie...

541
00:28:35,114 --> 00:28:37,483
And just for one moment,
wonder what it would be like?

542
00:28:39,385 --> 00:28:44,223
Beverly Jean, I don't want to
ever hear you talk like that.

543
00:28:44,256 --> 00:28:47,293
Oh, but you're only human.
It happens to everybody once.

544
00:28:47,326 --> 00:28:48,795
Maybe you've forgotten.

545
00:28:48,828 --> 00:28:50,797
What are you accusing me of?

546
00:28:51,998 --> 00:28:54,333
Nothing. Nothing.

547
00:28:54,366 --> 00:28:56,368
I haven't
forgotten a thing.

548
00:28:56,402 --> 00:29:01,507
I still remember our old
telephone number, 43668.

549
00:29:01,540 --> 00:29:03,075
We only had five digits then.

550
00:29:05,812 --> 00:29:08,047
Well, I'm, going to go see
how everybody's doing.

551
00:29:09,081 --> 00:29:11,150
-Honey?
-Hmm?

552
00:29:11,183 --> 00:29:14,220
Uh, can I be honest with you
about something?

553
00:29:14,253 --> 00:29:16,188
You won't be offended,
will you?

554
00:29:16,222 --> 00:29:18,324
No, not at all, Mother, what?

555
00:29:18,357 --> 00:29:21,260
I don't know
if it was your idea
or your friend Susan's,

556
00:29:21,293 --> 00:29:25,798
but, dear,
nobody uses butter anymore.

557
00:29:27,066 --> 00:29:28,467
You've been
to the market lately?

558
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:30,436
Everything is lite,
lite, lite.

559
00:29:31,537 --> 00:29:33,005
I'll remember that.

560
00:29:34,907 --> 00:29:36,142
Just a suggestion.

561
00:29:37,443 --> 00:29:38,477
Thank you.

562
00:29:43,249 --> 00:29:45,417
SUSAN: I always
do well with tomatoes.

563
00:29:45,451 --> 00:29:47,586
Last year, they were
coming out my ears.

564
00:29:47,619 --> 00:29:51,390
Well, now you have
two large red,
aroma and a yellow.

565
00:29:51,423 --> 00:29:53,059
Don't let me forget peppers.

566
00:29:53,092 --> 00:29:54,060
Oh, right here.

567
00:29:56,963 --> 00:29:58,898
How did your affair start?

568
00:29:58,931 --> 00:30:00,933
Did you see him
or did he see you?

569
00:30:04,036 --> 00:30:05,972
We worked
in the same building.

570
00:30:06,005 --> 00:30:08,307
We ran into each other
a couple of times.

571
00:30:08,340 --> 00:30:11,343
He was flat out direct,
didn't mince any words.

572
00:30:11,377 --> 00:30:13,445
He said if I wanted to get
to know him better,

573
00:30:13,479 --> 00:30:14,881
I shouldn't stand on ceremony.

574
00:30:14,914 --> 00:30:16,348
(SUSAN CHUCKLES)

575
00:30:16,382 --> 00:30:18,017
As if I ever did.

576
00:30:19,018 --> 00:30:20,486
I didn't even know
his last name

577
00:30:20,519 --> 00:30:22,621
till the second time
we took the hotel room.

578
00:30:22,654 --> 00:30:23,990
Didn't you notice
on his credit card?

579
00:30:24,490 --> 00:30:25,557
I paid.

580
00:30:26,893 --> 00:30:27,960
Oh.

581
00:30:29,228 --> 00:30:31,030
He worked in maintenance.

582
00:30:31,063 --> 00:30:33,232
When he wasn't at work,
he was at the gym.

583
00:30:33,265 --> 00:30:35,267
Muscles for days. (SIGHS)

584
00:30:35,301 --> 00:30:37,136
Oh, he may not have
invented sex,

585
00:30:37,169 --> 00:30:39,271
but, phew,
he sure improved on it.

586
00:30:39,305 --> 00:30:40,472
Okay, that's enough.

587
00:30:42,641 --> 00:30:45,111
A person gets bored
after fifteen years.

588
00:30:45,144 --> 00:30:46,512
I am not bored.

589
00:30:47,413 --> 00:30:49,581
How about some stringed beans?

590
00:30:49,615 --> 00:30:54,453
Excuse me, but you did
start the conversation, Jean.

591
00:30:54,486 --> 00:30:57,523
While you're rushing off
to change the subject
like I was sub-human,

592
00:30:57,556 --> 00:30:59,425
may I remind you,
you brought it up
in the first place?

593
00:31:00,092 --> 00:31:01,027
I know.

594
00:31:03,462 --> 00:31:05,464
I saw the way you and Tom
look at each other.

595
00:31:05,497 --> 00:31:06,632
I know what that look means.

596
00:31:06,665 --> 00:31:08,134
No, we have not done anything.

597
00:31:08,167 --> 00:31:09,301
Well, why don't you?

598
00:31:10,937 --> 00:31:12,404
You heard me.

599
00:31:12,438 --> 00:31:15,407
Go to bed with Tom.
Get it out of your system.

600
00:31:15,441 --> 00:31:17,309
They don't arrest you for it,
you know?

601
00:31:18,978 --> 00:31:20,646
No.

602
00:31:20,679 --> 00:31:22,248
But you pay for it
in other ways.

603
00:31:22,281 --> 00:31:23,249
You should know that.

604
00:31:25,084 --> 00:31:26,585
(SIGHS) Guess so.

605
00:31:29,355 --> 00:31:31,057
Sure seemed worth it
at the time.

606
00:31:31,723 --> 00:31:33,192
Senora Townsend.

607
00:31:34,994 --> 00:31:36,929
(SIGHS) Where would you
like the citrus?

608
00:31:36,963 --> 00:31:38,297
Uh, over by the fence, please.

609
00:31:38,330 --> 00:31:39,431
Okay.

610
00:31:39,465 --> 00:31:41,200
(PHONE RINGING)

611
00:31:41,233 --> 00:31:42,501
No, wait a minute.

612
00:31:42,534 --> 00:31:45,171
Uh, place it
right by the shed.
Okay, Jose?

613
00:31:45,204 --> 00:31:46,272
Okay.

614
00:31:46,305 --> 00:31:48,941
Jean, Tom's on the phone.
He wants to talk to you.

615
00:31:51,978 --> 00:31:54,213
Jose, I'll count those
with you.

616
00:31:55,314 --> 00:31:57,283
ROGER: Jean, it's Tom.

617
00:31:57,316 --> 00:31:58,584
He needs to talk to you.

618
00:32:18,737 --> 00:32:20,306
Maybe you shouldn't call here.

619
00:32:22,208 --> 00:32:23,009
What?

620
00:32:24,143 --> 00:32:25,111
Who is this?

621
00:32:26,312 --> 00:32:27,346
Mr. Reynolds!

622
00:32:28,380 --> 00:32:30,282
Hello, Tom!

623
00:32:30,316 --> 00:32:32,451
Mildew on your roses, uh-huh.

624
00:32:55,707 --> 00:32:57,409
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

625
00:33:01,680 --> 00:33:04,316
SUSAN:
I just loved this movie.
It's my all-time favorite.

626
00:33:05,184 --> 00:33:06,118
Ah!

627
00:33:07,386 --> 00:33:09,421
I mush every time I see it.

628
00:33:09,455 --> 00:33:11,057
My wild, sweet Cathy.

629
00:33:11,090 --> 00:33:14,226
Ugh, makes me
weak in the knees.

630
00:33:14,260 --> 00:33:17,063
Merle Oberon
was so beautiful.

631
00:33:17,096 --> 00:33:18,430
The clothes she wore.

632
00:33:18,464 --> 00:33:19,598
The woman hardly had a waist.

633
00:33:19,631 --> 00:33:22,634
And what a hunk
Olivier was.

634
00:33:22,668 --> 00:33:25,537
He was a great actor,
I never thought of him
as a hunk.

635
00:33:25,571 --> 00:33:27,473
(SCOFFS)
You wouldn't, we would.

636
00:33:27,506 --> 00:33:29,341
A major superior hunk.

637
00:33:29,375 --> 00:33:30,442
Trust us.

638
00:33:30,476 --> 00:33:34,113
Well, I have to get up
very early tomorrow morning.

639
00:33:34,713 --> 00:33:36,182
Good night, Tom.

640
00:33:36,215 --> 00:33:37,483
Glad you could
make it this week.

641
00:33:37,516 --> 00:33:38,584
Goodnight.

642
00:33:38,617 --> 00:33:41,120
Goodnight,
dear Heathcliff.

643
00:33:41,153 --> 00:33:42,621
-Ah!
-Lovely to meet you.

644
00:33:42,654 --> 00:33:44,123
You, too.
See you next week.

645
00:33:49,095 --> 00:33:50,629
He likes you, Jean.

646
00:33:50,662 --> 00:33:54,733
No, he's just a nice guy
who likes romantic films.

647
00:33:54,766 --> 00:33:57,436
I did think you were
a little formal, though,

648
00:33:57,469 --> 00:34:00,072
"Goodnight,
glad you could make it."

649
00:34:02,141 --> 00:34:03,409
I'm tired.

650
00:34:03,442 --> 00:34:05,377
I'll see you tomorrow.

651
00:34:05,411 --> 00:34:07,045
-Goodnight, honey.
-Bye.

652
00:34:07,746 --> 00:34:09,181
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

653
00:34:14,486 --> 00:34:15,621
(CHUCKLES)

654
00:35:26,258 --> 00:35:28,360
Oops. (SIGHS)

655
00:35:28,394 --> 00:35:29,928
-Trouble losing her?
-None.

656
00:35:29,961 --> 00:35:32,398
She made the light, I didn't.

657
00:35:32,431 --> 00:35:34,300
She always says
I drive too slowly.

658
00:35:34,333 --> 00:35:36,235
I've been looking forward
to this all week.

659
00:35:36,268 --> 00:35:37,903
I think I know a place
we can go.

660
00:35:37,936 --> 00:35:39,471
Where?

661
00:35:39,505 --> 00:35:40,539
Let me surprise you.

662
00:35:42,274 --> 00:35:44,243
I should take my car.
I should follow you.

663
00:35:49,815 --> 00:35:51,783
Oh, dear.

664
00:35:53,319 --> 00:35:56,255
I'm a bit of a klutz
when I'm nervous.

665
00:35:56,288 --> 00:35:59,425
I didn't make it two weeks
in Madame Gregoire's
ballet school for girls.

666
00:36:00,959 --> 00:36:02,361
Actually to
tell you the truth,

667
00:36:02,394 --> 00:36:04,330
I'm a bit of a klutz
when I'm not nervous.

668
00:36:05,664 --> 00:36:07,266
Excuse me. Yes.

669
00:36:09,701 --> 00:36:10,702
Oops.

670
00:36:13,839 --> 00:36:14,906
MAN: Here you go.

671
00:36:14,940 --> 00:36:16,975
JEAN: I was a lousy dancer,

672
00:36:17,008 --> 00:36:19,311
but Madame Gregoire
was from Atlanta

673
00:36:19,345 --> 00:36:20,812
and although
I couldn't do a plie,

674
00:36:20,846 --> 00:36:22,681
she could not speak
a word of French.

675
00:36:22,714 --> 00:36:24,450
(CHUCKLES)

676
00:36:24,483 --> 00:36:25,617
Would you like
something to eat?

677
00:36:25,651 --> 00:36:27,453
No. Thank you.

678
00:36:27,486 --> 00:36:28,820
Uh, you can.

679
00:36:28,854 --> 00:36:30,722
No, I had a sandwich
before I left home.

680
00:36:30,756 --> 00:36:32,491
Oh, what kind?

681
00:36:32,524 --> 00:36:34,726
Oh, scintillating, Jean!
(LAUGHS)

682
00:36:36,395 --> 00:36:38,964
What a wonderful
conversationalist!

683
00:36:38,997 --> 00:36:40,532
I'm really so bad
at all of this,

684
00:36:40,566 --> 00:36:42,734
all this chit chat
and small talk.

685
00:36:43,802 --> 00:36:44,936
I'm nervous.

686
00:36:46,605 --> 00:36:47,739
You're funny.

687
00:36:48,407 --> 00:36:49,408
Funny nervous.

688
00:36:50,409 --> 00:36:51,209
(SIGHS)

689
00:36:52,578 --> 00:36:54,413
I don't know why I'm here.

690
00:36:54,446 --> 00:36:56,948
I mean, I do, but I don't.

691
00:36:59,017 --> 00:37:01,987
Look, can I say something
really dumb?

692
00:37:07,293 --> 00:37:08,494
You are very pretty.

693
00:37:09,761 --> 00:37:10,762
(CHUCKLES)

694
00:37:11,563 --> 00:37:12,964
It's not dumb.

695
00:37:13,865 --> 00:37:16,402
Why do you think it's dumb?

696
00:37:16,435 --> 00:37:18,470
Well, I couldn't think
of a better way to say it.

697
00:37:19,538 --> 00:37:20,539
Thank you.

698
00:37:22,874 --> 00:37:24,175
I lied to Carol tonight.

699
00:37:24,209 --> 00:37:27,746
I told her I was going
to the office to work
after the film.

700
00:37:29,080 --> 00:37:30,649
I hate lying.

701
00:37:30,682 --> 00:37:32,384
I know
I'm guilty of it myself,

702
00:37:32,418 --> 00:37:35,687
but I've always taught Bess
to tell the truth,

703
00:37:35,721 --> 00:37:38,790
even if it means
hurting somebody's feelings.

704
00:37:38,824 --> 00:37:42,661
Sparing people's feelings
can become a lifelong job,

705
00:37:42,694 --> 00:37:45,364
and you lose yourself.

706
00:37:45,397 --> 00:37:48,767
I don't want her to spend
the rest of her life
pleasing others.

707
00:37:50,769 --> 00:37:52,538
-Have you?
-No.

708
00:37:53,505 --> 00:37:54,606
Yeah.

709
00:37:55,574 --> 00:37:56,575
A little.

710
00:37:59,110 --> 00:38:02,781
Roger's the nicest man I know.

711
00:38:02,814 --> 00:38:04,383
He would move heaven
and earth for me.

712
00:38:04,416 --> 00:38:07,786
He's strong, plays softball.

713
00:38:07,819 --> 00:38:10,522
Well, he used to play
on the softball team,
team broke up.

714
00:38:12,691 --> 00:38:13,759
Tell me about Carol.

715
00:38:14,893 --> 00:38:18,397
Well, she's decent, caring.

716
00:38:18,430 --> 00:38:20,732
She wanted to have
a lot of kids.

717
00:38:20,766 --> 00:38:24,970
When Kevin was born,
there were some complications
so we couldn't have anymore,

718
00:38:25,003 --> 00:38:26,805
which was a boon
for three-legged dogs.

719
00:38:28,540 --> 00:38:30,041
I'll explain that.

720
00:38:30,075 --> 00:38:34,045
See, there was a time
when we had two
three-legged dogs.

721
00:38:34,079 --> 00:38:36,648
No one else would take them in
so Carol did,

722
00:38:36,682 --> 00:38:39,551
separately,
several months apart.

723
00:38:39,585 --> 00:38:42,120
Till they died,
they just jumped
and hobbled around,

724
00:38:42,153 --> 00:38:43,955
happy as they could be.

725
00:38:43,989 --> 00:38:46,758
She loves
what nobody else does.

726
00:38:49,027 --> 00:38:51,863
She's not a saint,
but she's very kind.

727
00:38:54,165 --> 00:38:57,936
So, that's why I really
don't know why I'm here.

728
00:38:59,405 --> 00:39:00,839
But you're a bright woman...

729
00:39:02,974 --> 00:39:04,510
I was hoping
you could tell me.

730
00:39:06,778 --> 00:39:08,346
Not so bright, Tom.

731
00:39:10,148 --> 00:39:12,050
If I were, I would've run
that yellow light

732
00:39:12,083 --> 00:39:13,819
and followed Susan
as fast as I could.

733
00:39:13,852 --> 00:39:16,087
But do you know,
to hell with it.

734
00:39:16,121 --> 00:39:17,656
I don't think I care.

735
00:39:25,063 --> 00:39:27,098
I just wanted to see
what that would be like.

736
00:39:28,700 --> 00:39:30,101
Just curious?

737
00:39:31,537 --> 00:39:32,804
Yes.

738
00:39:35,541 --> 00:39:36,575
Still curious?

739
00:39:37,175 --> 00:39:38,644
Mmm-hmm.

740
00:40:02,868 --> 00:40:05,170
(BOTH BREATHING HEAVILY)

741
00:40:05,203 --> 00:40:06,572
Still curious?

742
00:40:09,140 --> 00:40:10,676
I got to go.

743
00:40:10,709 --> 00:40:13,712
Well, we solved
your curiosity,
what about mine?

744
00:40:13,745 --> 00:40:16,615
Tom, this has been
so much fun. Thank you!

745
00:40:16,648 --> 00:40:17,949
-Jean?
-Thank you.

746
00:40:22,621 --> 00:40:23,822
(DOOR OPENS)

747
00:40:40,972 --> 00:40:42,107
What time is it?

748
00:40:43,241 --> 00:40:44,643
-JEAN: Midnight.
-(GROANS)

749
00:40:46,545 --> 00:40:48,914
How do you stay up so late,
then get up so early?

750
00:40:51,550 --> 00:40:53,018
You're a better sleeper
than I am.

751
00:41:12,538 --> 00:41:13,872
(CHUCKLES)

752
00:41:13,905 --> 00:41:15,073
(DOOR OPENS)

753
00:41:17,976 --> 00:41:20,478
-Hi, heard you come in.
-Hi.

754
00:41:23,314 --> 00:41:25,984
I made a chocolate cake
from scratch.

755
00:41:26,017 --> 00:41:28,186
I just wanted to see
if I still knew how.

756
00:41:28,219 --> 00:41:30,689
How about a nice big piece?
Price is right.

757
00:41:30,722 --> 00:41:32,023
No, thanks.

758
00:41:33,859 --> 00:41:35,126
So, what did you
see tonight?

759
00:41:36,662 --> 00:41:37,829
Wuthering Heights.

760
00:41:37,863 --> 00:41:39,531
Ah, my Achilles heel.

761
00:41:40,632 --> 00:41:42,701
They assigned that to us
in high school.

762
00:41:42,734 --> 00:41:43,935
I could hardly
finish reading it.

763
00:41:43,969 --> 00:41:45,036
I never did see
the movie.

764
00:41:46,872 --> 00:41:48,807
Maybe I should
read the book again.

765
00:41:48,840 --> 00:41:50,642
All I remember are a lot
of people running around.

766
00:41:52,644 --> 00:41:54,580
Ah, what was it called?

767
