00:55:38,603 --> 00:55:40,505
Yeah, sounds good.

1021
00:55:52,983 --> 00:55:53,984
Honey.

1022
00:55:55,152 --> 00:55:58,756
I have to run over
to Hamilton on Friday.

1023
00:55:58,789 --> 00:56:00,625
Mr. Blake is looking at
a new site over there

1024
00:56:00,658 --> 00:56:01,992
and he wants me
to have a look.

1025
00:56:02,026 --> 00:56:03,628
Well, you want
a hitch hiker?

1026
00:56:03,661 --> 00:56:05,930
You could drop me at a mall,
any mall.

1027
00:56:05,963 --> 00:56:07,998
Oh, I'm not sure what the day
will bring.

1028
00:56:08,032 --> 00:56:11,168
Oh, I hate for you to have
to drive all that way
by yourself.

1029
00:56:11,201 --> 00:56:13,871
It's only a couple of hours.
I have a new Tosca 
to listen to.

1030
00:56:14,772 --> 00:56:16,907
Then you better go alone.

1031
00:56:16,941 --> 00:56:19,610
Why did you marry a low brow
like me anyway?

1032
00:56:19,644 --> 00:56:22,046
I hate opera, I don't read
any of the good books.

1033
00:56:23,581 --> 00:56:26,451
Guess I just married you
for the contrast.

1034
00:56:26,484 --> 00:56:27,952
There's plenty of that.

1035
00:56:27,985 --> 00:56:29,754
Going to meet Mark.
Bye, Mom, bye, Dad.

1036
00:56:29,787 --> 00:56:31,155
You be careful, Kev.

1037
00:56:31,188 --> 00:56:31,989
(DOOR CLOSING)

1038
00:56:36,494 --> 00:56:39,864
Kevin told me what you
said to him last night.

1039
00:56:39,897 --> 00:56:43,400
You know, that's one
of the things I love
most about you, Tom.

1040
00:56:44,635 --> 00:56:46,771
You always understand
the value of things.

1041
00:57:32,783 --> 00:57:34,552
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

1042
00:57:36,587 --> 00:57:39,089
Now, one of the most
common questions
in buying a rose

1043
00:57:39,123 --> 00:57:42,927
is whether to buy
a bare root or in container.

1044
00:57:42,960 --> 00:57:44,762
Does anyone here know
the difference?

1045
00:57:46,296 --> 00:57:48,065
Well, let me tell you.

1046
00:57:48,098 --> 00:57:51,869
A bare root goes directly
into your soil.

1047
00:57:51,902 --> 00:57:54,171
Now you carefully separate
the roots,

1048
00:57:55,540 --> 00:57:57,875
place the rose correctly,

1049
00:57:57,908 --> 00:57:59,944
ah, that's something else
we'll talk about,

1050
00:57:59,977 --> 00:58:03,013
and fill in with your soil.

1051
00:58:03,047 --> 00:58:06,551
Now, does anyone know
what a bud union is?

1052
00:58:08,152 --> 00:58:09,954
Ah, yes, young lady,
can you tell us?

1053
00:58:13,591 --> 00:58:15,693
Yes, do you know
what a bud union is?

1054
00:58:15,726 --> 00:58:18,162
The bud union is the heart
of the rose bush,

1055
00:58:18,195 --> 00:58:22,833
it's from the bud union
that the major
new growth develops,

1056
00:58:22,867 --> 00:58:25,002
if the conditions are right.

1057
00:58:25,035 --> 00:58:26,270
Ah, there's one thing
you've left out.

1058
00:58:26,303 --> 00:58:27,572
Hmm.

1059
00:58:27,605 --> 00:58:30,074
If you live in
a temperate climate,

1060
00:58:30,107 --> 00:58:34,078
the bud union can be placed
just above ground level,

1061
00:58:34,111 --> 00:58:37,147
like so, but if you live
in a cold climate...

1062
00:58:37,181 --> 00:58:39,917
You have to place it beneath
the surface where it's hidden.

1063
00:58:40,585 --> 00:58:42,019
Now, why is that?

1064
00:58:42,052 --> 00:58:43,854
The rose won't grow
if it's not hidden.

1065
00:58:44,955 --> 00:58:46,256
That's right.

1066
00:58:46,290 --> 00:58:49,126
Bud union's very fragile.

1067
00:58:49,159 --> 00:58:52,096
Hiding it protects it against
anything that might hurt it.

1068
00:58:56,701 --> 00:58:57,802
(LAUGHS)

1069
00:58:57,835 --> 00:58:59,737
(OPERA MUSIC PLAYING)

1070
00:59:10,380 --> 00:59:12,216
-Checking in, sir?
-Yes, I am.

1071
00:59:12,249 --> 00:59:15,152
Do you need help
with your luggage?

1072
00:59:15,185 --> 00:59:18,756
Well, actually, I do have
some things in the trunk
I'd like you to bring in.

1073
00:59:21,992 --> 00:59:23,127
Thank you.

1074
00:59:25,329 --> 00:59:26,731
Coming in now.

1075
00:59:28,999 --> 00:59:31,602
Oh, Vern, put that between
two burners, okay?

1076
00:59:31,636 --> 00:59:32,903
It's not going to work.

1077
00:59:32,937 --> 00:59:35,105
Well, it's going to have to,
it's the largest one
we've got.

1078
00:59:35,139 --> 00:59:36,373
Roast.

1079
00:59:36,406 --> 00:59:39,176
-Green beans.
-Potatoes.

1080
00:59:39,209 --> 00:59:40,377
Hi, honey,
you want something to eat?

1081
00:59:40,410 --> 00:59:41,746
It's for sick people.

1082
00:59:46,751 --> 00:59:49,353
-Oh, excuse me.
-It's okay.

1083
00:59:49,386 --> 00:59:50,755
MAN: Roast.
WOMAN: Green beans.

1084
00:59:54,825 --> 00:59:56,093
(VIDEO GAME NOISES)

1085
00:59:58,128 --> 00:59:59,296
Turn that off, please.

1086
00:59:59,329 --> 01:00:00,998
(LOWERS VOLUME)

1087
01:00:01,031 --> 01:00:02,700
-All the way.
-(SIGHS)

1088
01:00:05,335 --> 01:00:06,871
When are they all going
to leave?

1089
01:00:08,072 --> 01:00:10,808
We lost our kitchen today.

1090
01:00:10,841 --> 01:00:12,777
It was an old church,
and it was sold.

1091
01:00:12,810 --> 01:00:15,279
They're probably
going to tear it down.

1092
01:00:15,312 --> 01:00:19,083
We found a new kitchen,
but we can't move into it
until next week.

1093
01:00:20,217 --> 01:00:23,187
That left us with no place
to work,

1094
01:00:23,220 --> 01:00:25,923
and if we don't work,
a lot of sick people
won't eat.

1095
01:00:27,157 --> 01:00:28,926
You don't want that
to happen, do you?

1096
01:00:30,861 --> 01:00:33,163
The food we make is healthy,
Kevin.

1097
01:00:33,197 --> 01:00:35,265
You're not going
to catch anything
by being around it

1098
01:00:35,299 --> 01:00:36,867
or around us,

1099
01:00:36,901 --> 01:00:39,269
or around the people
we make it for.

1100
01:00:41,038 --> 01:00:42,907
Where's Dad?

1101
01:00:42,940 --> 01:00:44,909
Daddy had to go to Hamilton
on a job,

1102
01:00:44,942 --> 01:00:46,711
he's going to be home
really late.

1103
01:01:16,874 --> 01:01:18,242
(INAUDIBLE)

1104
01:01:21,078 --> 01:01:22,146
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

1105
01:01:24,181 --> 01:01:25,883
Climbing Rose nursery.

1106
01:01:25,916 --> 01:01:27,985
Uh, Yes, Jean Townsend,
please.

1107
01:01:28,018 --> 01:01:29,887
She's not in today.
Could I take a...

1108
01:03:05,349 --> 01:03:06,951
Are you checking in?

1109
01:03:09,119 --> 01:03:10,888
-Checking in, ma'am?
-Yes.

1110
01:03:25,569 --> 01:03:27,004
MAN: Room 510.
I'll take...

1111
01:03:31,275 --> 01:03:32,376
(BEEPS)

1112
01:03:32,409 --> 01:03:33,477
WOMAN: Operator.

1113
01:03:33,510 --> 01:03:35,312
Could I have
an outside line, please?

1114
01:03:35,345 --> 01:03:36,914
Hello?

1115
01:03:36,947 --> 01:03:39,149
JEAN: Just checking in 
 on everybody.

1116
01:03:39,183 --> 01:03:41,886
Well, we've had, um,
a little emergency.

1117
01:03:41,919 --> 01:03:43,587
What happened, Roger?

1118
01:03:43,620 --> 01:03:44,989
I don't really know.

1119
01:03:45,022 --> 01:03:46,991
She only wants
to talk about it with you.

1120
01:03:47,024 --> 01:03:48,125
Here.

1121
01:03:51,061 --> 01:03:52,096
Hi, Mom.

1122
01:03:52,129 --> 01:03:53,630
What happened, honey?

1123
01:03:53,663 --> 01:03:56,166
Luther's parents 
 are out of town.

1124
01:03:56,200 --> 01:03:58,268
He wanted me
to come home with him.
(SNIFFLING)

1125
01:03:58,302 --> 01:03:59,469
Guess why?

1126
01:03:59,503 --> 01:04:01,071
I said no.

1127
01:04:01,105 --> 01:04:03,607
He said, 
 either I slept with him 
 or found a new boyfriend.

1128
01:04:04,942 --> 01:04:06,276
I'll come right home,
right now.

1129
01:04:06,310 --> 01:04:08,578
(SOBBING) I'm okay, Mom,
you don't have to.

1130
01:04:08,612 --> 01:04:11,381
No, I can.
I can and I'll be there
in a few hours.

1131
01:04:11,415 --> 01:04:14,184
Mom! You sound worse 
 than me. I'm okay.

1132
01:04:14,218 --> 01:04:16,520
You did the right thing,
Bess.

1133
01:04:16,553 --> 01:04:20,090
Mom, I cried all afternoon.
(SNIFFLING)

1134
01:04:20,958 --> 01:04:22,659
That felt really good.

1135
01:04:22,692 --> 01:04:25,395
And you know what I realized?

1136
01:04:25,429 --> 01:04:30,300
There's a lot of boys
and some of them
don't have stupid names.

1137
01:04:30,334 --> 01:04:34,304
Luther sounds like a dog, 
 which isn't far 
 from the truth.

1138
01:04:35,439 --> 01:04:37,374
I'm so proud of you, Bess.

1139
01:04:40,410 --> 01:04:43,047
I wish I was as smart as you
when I was your age.

1140
01:04:44,648 --> 01:04:46,183
I'll see you tomorrow.

1141
01:04:48,118 --> 01:04:50,387
Sleep tight, don't let
the bed bugs get ya.

1142
01:04:50,420 --> 01:04:52,289
(CHUCKLES)
There aren't any, Mom.

1143
01:04:52,322 --> 01:04:54,091
-Bess? 
 -(SNIFFLING) Yeah?

1144
01:04:56,160 --> 01:04:56,994
I love you.

1145
01:04:58,195 --> 01:05:01,098
I love you, too, Mom.
(SNIFFLES) Bye.

1146
01:05:02,099 --> 01:05:03,333
Bye.

1147
01:05:03,367 --> 01:05:04,668
(SOBBING)

1148
01:05:09,506 --> 01:05:10,907
(SIGHS)

1149
01:05:18,215 --> 01:05:19,249
(PHONE RINGING)

1150
01:05:22,386 --> 01:05:23,988
WOMAN: Operator.

1151
01:05:24,021 --> 01:05:25,522
Mr. Doster's room, please.

1152
01:05:25,555 --> 01:05:26,991
(PHONE RINGING)

1153
01:05:27,024 --> 01:05:28,125
TOM: Hello?

1154
01:05:29,259 --> 01:05:30,327
I'm here.

1155
01:05:38,768 --> 01:05:40,237
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

1156
01:05:50,014 --> 01:05:52,616
It's like Christmas.

1157
01:05:52,649 --> 01:05:54,718
TOM: Well, I wanted it
to be beautiful for you.

1158
01:05:58,455 --> 01:06:00,124
You must have spent a fortune.

1159
01:06:00,157 --> 01:06:02,526
Well, I spent
a fortune on this.

1160
01:06:02,559 --> 01:06:05,129
I went and got the champagne,
the flowers, and everything,

1161
01:06:05,162 --> 01:06:06,696
and I forgot the glasses.

1162
01:06:06,730 --> 01:06:08,999
But found these
in the bathroom.

1163
01:06:11,368 --> 01:06:15,139
I'm not... I'm not ready yet.

1164
01:06:15,172 --> 01:06:17,007
Could we, maybe,
take that downstairs?

1165
01:06:18,242 --> 01:06:19,276
Just for a little while.

1166
01:06:21,078 --> 01:06:22,079
Sure.

1167
01:06:23,047 --> 01:06:24,014
We could talk.

1168
01:06:24,781 --> 01:06:27,317
Yeah.

1169
01:06:27,351 --> 01:06:31,621
You are the only thing
I have been able
to think about.

1170
01:06:31,655 --> 01:06:34,091
I've been walking
around the office,
and the house,

1171
01:06:34,124 --> 01:06:37,227
hoping that I was doing
a good job faking it.

1172
01:06:37,261 --> 01:06:41,098
I don't think anyone realized
how really far away I was.

1173
01:06:44,601 --> 01:06:46,103
Why me, Tom?

1174
01:06:47,537 --> 01:06:49,139
What do you mean?

1175
01:06:51,241 --> 01:06:55,112
You've met other women before,
younger, prettier.

1176
01:06:55,145 --> 01:06:57,147
You probably had
a lot of choices.

1177
01:06:58,715 --> 01:07:00,417
I don't know.

1178
01:07:00,450 --> 01:07:02,652
(CHUCKING) Oh, come on,
you have.

1179
01:07:04,121 --> 01:07:06,323
Come on.

1180
01:07:06,356 --> 01:07:09,126
You've never spent any time
with anybody other than Carol?

1181
01:07:11,561 --> 01:07:14,131
Quick hour in a hotel,
couple of drinks?

1182
01:07:15,665 --> 01:07:18,568
Oh, you probably have,
it's just slipped your mind.

1183
01:07:19,536 --> 01:07:21,171
You're the first.

1184
01:07:23,573 --> 01:07:25,742
(SIGHS)

1185
01:07:25,775 --> 01:07:27,811
Roger is the only man
I have ever been with.

1186
01:07:29,446 --> 01:07:30,580
Can you believe that?

1187
01:07:31,581 --> 01:07:33,283
In this day and age?

1188
01:07:33,317 --> 01:07:35,252
You probably think I'm weird.

1189
01:07:35,285 --> 01:07:36,453
No, I don't.

1190
01:07:39,823 --> 01:07:43,460
I'm... I'm probably
what they call an anachronism?

1191
01:07:43,493 --> 01:07:46,496
Is that right?
Anachronism, yeah.

1192
01:07:46,530 --> 01:07:49,133
Someone who doesn't fit
into their time
and their surroundings.

1193
01:07:51,635 --> 01:07:53,637
A '90s woman who has only
been with one man.

1194
01:07:53,670 --> 01:07:55,105
(JEAN CHUCKLES)

1195
01:07:57,241 --> 01:07:58,642
(SIGHS)

1196
01:07:58,675 --> 01:08:02,179
Roger would cross the earth
for me if I asked him to,

1197
01:08:02,212 --> 01:08:04,181
and he'd never ask why.

1198
01:08:07,151 --> 01:08:09,519
I love him for that,

1199
01:08:09,553 --> 01:08:10,820
the way he trusts me.

1200
01:08:13,690 --> 01:08:16,126
And sometimes
I resent him...

1201
01:08:18,595 --> 01:08:20,564
For trusting me so much.

1202
01:08:23,600 --> 01:08:25,835
See, I don't only cry
in movies.

1203
01:08:28,772 --> 01:08:30,307
No, thank you.

1204
01:08:34,211 --> 01:08:35,645
Maybe you'd like
to get some air, huh?

1205
01:08:35,679 --> 01:08:37,147
Mmm-hmm.

1206
01:08:41,251 --> 01:08:43,287
JEAN: You made the room
look like a garden.

1207
01:08:44,454 --> 01:08:46,656
TOM: Well, I wanted you
to feel at home.

1208
01:08:46,690 --> 01:08:49,359
Thought if I filled the room
with flowers,

1209
01:08:49,393 --> 01:08:52,362
think that you were outside,
somewhere off in a forest.

1210
01:08:53,963 --> 01:08:56,833
I always had a fantasy
about making love outside.

1211
01:08:56,866 --> 01:08:58,635
Have you ever done that?

1212
01:08:58,668 --> 01:09:01,638
I don't think so,
I don't remember.

1213
01:09:01,671 --> 01:09:03,207
On cool wet grass,

1214
01:09:03,240 --> 01:09:05,542
with nobody around
for miles and miles,

1215
01:09:05,575 --> 01:09:07,344
in a beautiful garden.

1216
01:09:07,377 --> 01:09:08,745
(CHUCKLES)

1217
01:09:08,778 --> 01:09:12,949
I always seem
to get emotional
in the dark.

1218
01:09:12,982 --> 01:09:16,520
The darkness of the theater
where nobody can see me and...

1219
01:09:18,355 --> 01:09:19,456
Here.

1220
01:09:25,295 --> 01:09:27,163
I've wondered how
you would feel...

1221
01:09:28,298 --> 01:09:29,933
So many times.

1222
01:09:29,966 --> 01:09:31,368
In my mind...

1223
01:09:33,002 --> 01:09:34,404
I've touched you.

1224
01:09:35,272 --> 01:09:36,373
Hold me, Tom.

1225
01:09:40,344 --> 01:09:41,345
(SIGHS)

1226
01:09:42,612 --> 01:09:43,880
Oh, I'm here.

1227
01:09:44,814 --> 01:09:46,950
I don't ever want you to go.

1228
01:09:48,252 --> 01:09:50,354
I don't ever want
to be away from you.

1229
01:09:50,387 --> 01:09:52,389
I don't ever want to be
not touching you.

1230
01:09:52,422 --> 01:09:53,457
Promise me, Tom.

1231
01:09:56,560 --> 01:09:57,861
I promise you.

1232
01:09:59,529 --> 01:10:01,665
I'm thinking maybe this is
what heaven's like.

1233
01:10:03,267 --> 01:10:04,401
Warm and safe.

1234
01:10:06,603 --> 01:10:08,204
I love you.

1235
01:10:15,945 --> 01:10:18,848
Ah, God, Jean,
you are so warm.

1236
01:10:21,785 --> 01:10:23,820
I've done this in my mind,
a hundred times.

1237
01:10:24,854 --> 01:10:26,856
Hundred times before now.

1238
01:10:30,560 --> 01:10:31,728
Let's go up.

1239
01:10:41,538 --> 01:10:43,607
I'm sorry, I'm so sorry.

1240
01:10:43,640 --> 01:10:45,875
I can't... I can't do this.

1241
01:10:45,909 --> 01:10:47,811
-(THUNDER RUMBLING)
-It's okay.

1242
01:10:47,844 --> 01:10:49,846
No, it's not okay.

1243
01:10:49,879 --> 01:10:52,349
It would be so easy
if I didn't love Roger.

1244
01:10:52,382 --> 01:10:53,483
You want to just come in?

1245
01:10:53,517 --> 01:10:56,453
No, see,
I've never been good
at keeping secrets,

1246
01:10:56,486 --> 01:10:58,355
I'd have to keep this one
for the rest of my life.

1247
01:10:58,388 --> 01:11:00,757
I'm sorry. I'm so scared,
I just can't.

1248
01:11:00,790 --> 01:11:01,858
I'm so sorry.

1249
01:11:03,059 --> 01:11:04,428
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1250
01:11:04,461 --> 01:11:05,529
Jean, wait.

1251
01:11:07,831 --> 01:11:09,499
We could say
we couldn't help it.

1252
01:11:09,533 --> 01:11:10,767
Couldn't we, Tom?

1253
01:11:10,800 --> 01:11:12,702
Isn't that what other
people say?

1254
01:11:12,736 --> 01:11:14,904
That something happened,
they didn't know what?

1255
01:11:14,938 --> 01:11:16,406
You hear it all the time.

1256
01:11:17,907 --> 01:11:19,075
Oh, only if I could
stop thinking,

1257
01:11:19,108 --> 01:11:21,445
just stop thinking
for a few seconds.

1258
01:11:22,546 --> 01:11:23,680
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1259
01:11:31,488 --> 01:11:32,789
(GROANING)

1260
01:11:32,822 --> 01:11:34,358
Ow!

1261
01:11:34,391 --> 01:11:35,392
Oh.

1262
01:11:35,959 --> 01:11:37,361
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1263
01:11:38,395 --> 01:11:39,463
(PANTING)

1264
01:11:39,496 --> 01:11:40,497
Oh!

1265
01:11:42,432 --> 01:11:43,500
(GASPS)

1266
01:11:46,035 --> 01:11:47,904
I don't have the ticket.

1267
01:11:47,937 --> 01:11:50,073
That's okay.
I never forget
a car or a face.

1268
01:11:50,974 --> 01:11:52,008
(PANTING)

1269
01:12:04,120 --> 01:12:05,422
(SOBBING)

1270
01:12:08,157 --> 01:12:09,426
(SNIFFLING)

1271
01:12:09,459 --> 01:12:10,093
(CAR HONKING)

1272
01:12:10,126 --> 01:12:11,327
(GASPS)

1273
01:12:14,798 --> 01:12:15,899
(WHIMPERING)

1274
01:12:36,019 --> 01:12:37,587
(SIGHS)

1275
01:12:37,621 --> 01:12:39,889
Oh, Jean, what a mess you are.

1276
01:12:41,891 --> 01:12:43,560
What a mess.

1277
01:12:43,593 --> 01:12:45,028
Look at her.

1278
01:12:45,995 --> 01:12:47,397
Look at me.

1279
01:12:52,969 --> 01:12:54,438
(DIALING)

1280
01:12:56,606 --> 01:12:58,141
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

1281
01:13:01,144 --> 01:13:02,446
Hello?

1282
01:13:02,479 --> 01:13:03,547
(SOBBING)

1283
01:13:07,016 --> 01:13:09,118
Wait a minute, it's okay.

1284
01:13:10,787 --> 01:13:12,055
It's all right.

1285
01:13:12,822 --> 01:13:13,957
(SIGHS)

1286
01:13:14,524 --> 01:13:15,792
(SOBBING)

1287
01:13:15,825 --> 01:13:17,527
I just came in
from the balcony.

1288
01:13:18,828 --> 01:13:20,497
The sky is so clear
after it rains.

1289
01:13:20,530 --> 01:13:21,631
(JEAN SIGHS)

1290
01:13:21,665 --> 01:13:22,866
Stars everywhere.

1291
01:13:24,734 --> 01:13:26,069
Don't see stars 
 very much here.

1292
01:13:28,738 --> 01:13:30,139
I'm sorry I ran away.

1293
01:13:32,809 --> 01:13:35,545
Sometimes when we can't find 
 words to explain, we run.

1294
01:13:35,579 --> 01:13:36,780
(SIGHS)

1295
01:13:38,081 --> 01:13:39,749
I can't live
like this anymore.

1296
01:13:41,885 --> 01:13:43,587
I'm doing things
I've never done,

1297
01:13:43,620 --> 01:13:44,754
I mean, lying.

1298
01:13:44,788 --> 01:13:46,490
I'm making up excuses.

1299
01:13:46,523 --> 01:13:48,692
I think people are seeing
how strange I'm acting.

1300
01:13:49,759 --> 01:13:52,596
(SIGHS)

1301
01:13:52,629 --> 01:13:54,964
I'm afraid to say anything
'cause I'm afraid
it's going to be wrong

1302
01:13:54,998 --> 01:13:55,999
and something will slip out.

1303
01:13:58,101 --> 01:13:59,503
Where are you?

1304
01:13:59,536 --> 01:14:02,038
(SIGHS) Some motel
off the freeway.

1305
01:14:02,972 --> 01:14:04,841
The Bates Motel.

1306
01:14:04,874 --> 01:14:05,909
(CHUCKLES)

1307
01:14:05,942 --> 01:14:06,876
(JEAN SNIFFLING)

1308
01:14:08,745 --> 01:14:09,979
You have a balcony?

1309
01:14:13,883 --> 01:14:14,984
Yeah.

1310
01:14:21,858 --> 01:14:22,859
Look up.

1311
01:14:26,763 --> 01:14:27,831
It's clear.

1312
01:14:27,864 --> 01:14:28,898
I see the stars.

1313
01:14:32,802 --> 01:14:34,037
Hold me, Tom.

1314
01:14:35,839 --> 01:14:37,907
Put your arms around me.

1315
01:14:41,177 --> 01:14:42,245
You feel them?

1316
01:14:44,180 --> 01:14:45,682
Mmm-hmm.

1317
01:14:47,283 --> 01:14:48,885
I'm holding you.

1318
01:14:50,820 --> 01:14:54,123
From the sea to the sea
I'm holding you
as close as I can.

1319
01:14:56,626 --> 01:14:58,161
What do we do now?

1320
01:15:00,897 --> 01:15:02,265
I wish I knew, Jean.

1321
01:15:04,133 --> 01:15:05,635
I wish I knew.

1322
01:15:06,035 --> 01:15:07,070
(SIGHS)

1323
01:15:16,580 --> 01:15:18,548
Hey, Kev, did you
get something to eat?

1324
01:15:18,582 --> 01:15:20,784
Mom made some chicken
before she left.

1325
01:15:20,817 --> 01:15:22,085
Good.

1326
01:15:22,118 --> 01:15:23,286
Hey, Dad.

1327
01:15:26,923 --> 01:15:28,725
Can a man and a woman
just be friends?

1328
01:15:30,093 --> 01:15:31,160
Yes.

1329
01:15:32,295 --> 01:15:33,597
Why do you ask that?

1330
01:15:36,332 --> 01:15:38,968
Hey.

1331
01:15:39,002 --> 01:15:42,706
Come on, you know
there's nothing off limits
between us.

1332
01:15:46,242 --> 01:15:48,044
I found this in your car.

1333
01:15:51,047 --> 01:15:52,949
Business cards
and a perfume bottle.

1334
01:16:00,657 --> 01:16:03,827
Well, Jean went to
the film series with me,

1335
01:16:03,860 --> 01:16:05,895
and I gave her a ride
in my car,

1336
01:16:05,929 --> 01:16:10,233
and as I recall,
she accidentally
spilled her bag.

1337
01:16:10,266 --> 01:16:12,636
So, you and her
are friends then?

1338
01:16:12,669 --> 01:16:16,072
Yeah. And I hope
we'll always be that.

1339
01:16:17,340 --> 01:16:18,207
That's all?

1340
01:16:19,643 --> 01:16:21,811
Yeah, just good friends.

1341
01:16:23,246 --> 01:16:24,280
Very good friends.

1342
01:16:26,883 --> 01:16:28,918
I think I understand now.

1343
01:16:28,952 --> 01:16:30,654
Can I have some
ice cream, Dad?

1344
01:16:30,687 --> 01:16:31,821
Sure.

1345
01:16:39,428 --> 01:16:41,931
BESS: Uh, Mom,
can you pass the vegetables?

1346
01:16:43,232 --> 01:16:46,002
-Mom?
-Yes, honey.

1347
01:16:46,035 --> 01:16:48,337
Um, can you please pass
the vegetables?

1348
01:16:48,371 --> 01:16:50,006
Oh, yeah.

1349
01:16:51,207 --> 01:16:52,275
I made dessert.

1350
01:16:52,308 --> 01:16:53,810
Oh, I'm too fat.

1351
01:16:54,711 --> 01:16:56,079
You are not too fat.

1352
01:16:56,112 --> 01:16:59,248
-Roger! You want dessert?
-ROGER: Later.

1353
01:16:59,282 --> 01:17:00,750
Are you going
to the movies tonight?

1354
01:17:00,784 --> 01:17:02,852
Yeah, have to. Last one.

1355
01:17:03,887 --> 01:17:05,154
All young people think
they're fat.

1356
01:17:05,889 --> 01:17:07,356
You're a six.

1357
01:17:07,390 --> 01:17:09,192
Do you know how many people
would love to be a six?

1358
01:17:09,225 --> 01:17:11,294
Well, what do you think?

1359
01:17:11,327 --> 01:17:12,261
Uh? (CHUCKLING)

1360
01:17:13,029 --> 01:17:14,931
Oh, jeez!

1361
01:17:14,964 --> 01:17:18,101
York Groove All Stars
are going to try again.

1362
01:17:18,134 --> 01:17:20,003
First practice
is this Saturday.

1363
01:17:20,036 --> 01:17:21,938
Danny Meyer
called all the guys,

1364
01:17:21,971 --> 01:17:23,172
everyone's over
their bruised egos.

1365
01:17:23,206 --> 01:17:24,407
We are ready
to bruise them again.

1366
01:17:24,440 --> 01:17:25,608
Uh, Dad, your pants are split.

1367
01:17:25,641 --> 01:17:28,277
Oh, yeah. I was hoping,
maybe, you could sew
it up for me.

1368
01:17:28,311 --> 01:17:29,946
Sure, when I get home.

1369
01:17:31,347 --> 01:17:33,683
Is, um, Susan
going tonight?

1370
01:17:35,284 --> 01:17:38,087
Or is she out on an emergency
session with her shrink?

1371
01:17:39,322 --> 01:17:41,991
Susan, yeah,
she'll be there.

1372
01:17:42,025 --> 01:17:43,192
WOMAN: When you were out 
 in the real country,

1373
01:17:43,226 --> 01:17:46,195
I think it was a few miles 
 beyond Greyfield,

1374
01:17:46,229 --> 01:17:49,198
we stopped the car 
 just outside a village 
 and got out.

1375
01:17:49,232 --> 01:17:51,367
There was a little bridge 
 and a stream,

1376
01:17:51,400 --> 01:17:53,169
and the sun was making 
 an effort to come out,

1377
01:17:53,202 --> 01:17:56,005
but really not succeeding 
 very well.

1378
01:17:56,039 --> 01:17:57,807
We leaned on the parapet 
 of the bridge

1379
01:17:57,841 --> 01:17:59,709
and looked down 
 into the water.

1380
01:17:59,743 --> 01:18:02,111
I shivered, and Alec 
 put his arm around me.

1381
01:18:02,145 --> 01:18:04,848
MAN: Cold? 
WOMAN: No, not really.

1382
01:18:04,881 --> 01:18:06,049
MAN: Happy?

1383
01:18:09,385 --> 01:18:10,720
WOMAN: No, not really.

1384
01:18:12,521 --> 01:18:15,759
I knew exactly what you 
 were going to say.

1385
01:18:15,792 --> 01:18:17,093
That it isn't worth it.

1386
01:18:18,762 --> 01:18:20,930
That the furtiveness 
 and lying

1387
01:18:20,964 --> 01:18:23,332
outweigh the happiness 
 we might have together.

1388
01:18:23,366 --> 01:18:24,868
Isn't that it?

1389
01:18:25,769 --> 01:18:27,103
Something like that.

1390
01:18:31,207 --> 01:18:34,778
MAN:
 I want to ask you something, 
 just to reassure myself.

1391
01:18:34,811 --> 01:18:36,112
WOMAN: What is it?

1392
01:18:37,246 --> 01:18:39,816
MAN: It is true for you, 
 isn't it?

1393
01:18:39,849 --> 01:18:41,851
This overwhelming feeling 
 we have for each other.

1394
01:18:41,885 --> 01:18:44,087
It's as true for you 
 as it is for me, isn't it?

1395
01:18:45,121 --> 01:18:46,489
WOMAN: Yes, it's true.

1396
01:18:53,562 --> 01:18:55,198
SUSAN: Was Brief Encounter 
after Gone with the Wind?

1397
01:18:56,933 --> 01:18:58,434
-What?
-Which came first?

1398
01:18:58,467 --> 01:18:59,903
Brief Encounter or
 Gone with the Wind?

1399
01:18:59,936 --> 01:19:01,270
Gone with the Wind, 
 I think.

1400
01:19:01,304 --> 01:19:05,008
Trevor Howard
doesn't look like he did
in Gone with the Wind.

1401
01:19:05,041 --> 01:19:07,276
Trevor Howard wasn't
in Gone with the Wind.

1402
01:19:07,310 --> 01:19:09,879
Leslie Howard
was in Gone with the Wind.

1403
01:19:09,913 --> 01:19:11,080
Really?

1404
01:19:11,114 --> 01:19:13,216
I never knew they
were different people.

1405
01:19:13,249 --> 01:19:14,818
Leslie Howard, Trevor Howard.

1406
01:19:15,819 --> 01:19:17,987
Well, what do you know.

1407
01:19:18,021 --> 01:19:19,122
They're both English,
aren't they?

1408
01:19:20,389 --> 01:19:21,958
They were.

1409
01:19:21,991 --> 01:19:23,526
They're both dead now.

1410
01:19:23,559 --> 01:19:25,294
SUSAN: Well,
there you have it.

1411
01:19:25,328 --> 01:19:26,963
It's the way
the English talk...

1412
01:19:26,996 --> 01:19:28,497
(ENGLISH ACCENT)
...from the bottom
of their throats.

1413
01:19:28,531 --> 01:19:30,133
(NORMAL VOICE)
They all sound alike.

1414
01:19:35,338 --> 01:19:37,506
Excuse me, I'll be right back.

1415
01:19:37,540 --> 01:19:40,009
Of course,
you'll talk about me
while I'm gone.

1416
01:19:40,043 --> 01:19:42,812
Sticks and stones
can break my bones,
but words can never hurt me.

1417
01:19:42,846 --> 01:19:45,114
I'm not ignorant, you know.

1418
01:19:45,148 --> 01:19:47,116
Just because
I didn't know the difference

1419
01:19:47,150 --> 01:19:48,584
between Leslie Howard
and Trevor Howard,

1420
01:19:48,617 --> 01:19:50,453
doesn't mean I haven't
been well educated.

1421
01:19:53,222 --> 01:19:56,059
Actually, I was voted
most likely to succeed.

1422
01:19:58,127 --> 01:20:00,029
But I got married instead.

1423
01:20:02,966 --> 01:20:03,967
(CHUCKLES)

1424
01:20:06,069 --> 01:20:07,370
It was a lovely movie.

1425
01:20:07,403 --> 01:20:08,905
Yes, it was.

1426
01:20:09,638 --> 01:20:11,307
I'd never seen
that one before.

1427
01:20:11,340 --> 01:20:13,042
Yeah, I saw it a long ago,

1428
01:20:13,076 --> 01:20:14,377
but I remember
it being in color.

1429
01:20:14,410 --> 01:20:16,980
I don't remember it being
in black and white.

1430
01:20:17,013 --> 01:20:19,348
Oh, they didn't seem
to film much in color then,

1431
01:20:19,382 --> 01:20:20,483
but not much, yeah.

1432
01:20:23,887 --> 01:20:25,188
-Listen, I got a call...
-You know, I was thinking...

1433
01:20:25,221 --> 01:20:26,455
Oh, I'm sorry,
you go first.

1434
01:20:26,489 --> 01:20:28,257
-No, I'm sorry, go ahead.
-No, you.

1435
01:20:31,394 --> 01:20:33,196
I got a call a couple
of days ago
from a company...

1436
01:20:33,229 --> 01:20:35,131
SUSAN:
That's it for me, folks.

1437
01:20:35,164 --> 01:20:37,934
It was really nice
to meet you, Tom.

1438
01:20:37,967 --> 01:20:39,568
It was nice to meet you, too.

1439
01:20:40,469 --> 01:20:42,872
You two stay. I'm tired.

1440
01:20:42,906 --> 01:20:45,008
No, I... I have to go, too.

1441
01:20:45,041 --> 01:20:46,976
Goodbye.
I mean goodnight.

1442
01:20:47,010 --> 01:20:48,912
Don't let me break up
the party.

1443
01:20:48,945 --> 01:20:51,480
Oh, it's all right.
I think the evening's over.

1444
01:20:53,082 --> 01:20:54,250
Goodnight.

1445
01:20:58,021 --> 01:20:59,655
JOSE: Senora Townsend!

1446
01:20:59,688 --> 01:21:01,557
-Yeah?
 -Telefono.

1447
01:21:01,590 --> 01:21:03,259
-Someone named Tom?
-Ah.

1448
01:21:04,293 --> 01:21:05,228
(CHUCKLES)

1449
01:21:10,666 --> 01:21:12,268
Still having
mildew problems, huh?

1450
01:21:13,669 --> 01:21:15,571
Well, I'm having
some problems,

1451
01:21:15,604 --> 01:21:17,006
but mildew
isn't one of them.

1452
01:21:18,074 --> 01:21:19,442
Oh, I...

1453
01:21:19,475 --> 01:21:21,644
Look, Jean,
I need to see you.

1454
01:21:23,012 --> 01:21:24,613
I have to see you, too.

1455
01:21:24,647 --> 01:21:26,182
When?

1456
01:21:26,215 --> 01:21:28,384
Now. Right now.

1457
01:21:28,417 --> 01:21:30,954
Um, city park, 
 by the rose garden.

1458
01:21:32,355 --> 01:21:34,223
(DIAL TONE)

1459
01:21:34,257 --> 01:21:36,125
Um, Roger?

1460
01:21:37,460 --> 01:21:39,963
I just got a call
and I have to run over
to Taylor's

1461
01:21:39,996 --> 01:21:42,265
to make a bid
for some landscaping.

1462
01:21:42,298 --> 01:21:44,367
Hope they don't need it soon,
we are up to our ears.

1463
01:21:44,400 --> 01:21:45,969
No, I don't think so.

1464
01:21:46,002 --> 01:21:48,604
I think they've still
got to put in their pool.

1465
01:21:48,637 --> 01:21:51,540
You mind going
and picking up Bess
after school, if I'm late?

1466
01:21:51,574 --> 01:21:52,608
Sure.

1467
01:21:52,641 --> 01:21:54,377
Thank you.

1468
01:21:54,410 --> 01:21:55,511
See you later.

1469
01:22:25,208 --> 01:22:26,209
(SIGHS)

1470
01:22:29,578 --> 01:22:31,047
You have one, too.

1471
01:22:37,220 --> 01:22:40,023
I don't quite know
how to say this.

1472
01:22:40,056 --> 01:22:42,158
(SOBBING) Oh, come on,
Beverly Jean, just say it.

1473
01:22:45,028 --> 01:22:47,496
I can't see you
after this anymore, Tom.

1474
01:22:47,530 --> 01:22:48,664
I just can't.

1475
01:22:52,801 --> 01:22:55,771
It's not true, I can,
but I won't.

1476
01:22:55,804 --> 01:22:57,040
I won't.

1477
01:22:59,142 --> 01:23:01,210
Seems to be the only thing
that's right.

1478
01:23:01,244 --> 01:23:04,680
(SNIFFLING)
And I don't mean just right,
I mean possible.

1479
01:23:08,717 --> 01:23:10,053
Are you angry with me?

1480
01:23:13,089 --> 01:23:14,123
No.

1481
01:23:18,194 --> 01:23:19,228
You are.

1482
01:23:24,633 --> 01:23:26,035
I'm moving, Jean.

1483
01:23:27,370 --> 01:23:29,572
I mean...

1484
01:23:29,605 --> 01:23:31,474
We're moving,
Carol, Kevin and I.

1485
01:23:34,210 --> 01:23:36,545
I wanted to tell you
the other night,

1486
01:23:36,579 --> 01:23:38,114
but I couldn't.

1487
01:23:41,584 --> 01:23:43,152
A few months ago
I got an offer

1488
01:23:43,186 --> 01:23:44,787
from a company
in Seattle.

1489
01:23:45,654 --> 01:23:48,157
I turned them down.

1490
01:23:48,191 --> 01:23:50,193
Last week,
I called them back

1491
01:23:50,226 --> 01:23:52,428
and said if they were
still interested,

1492
01:23:53,429 --> 01:23:55,231
I was.

1493
01:23:55,264 --> 01:23:56,799
You really have to do that?
Move away?

1494
01:24:00,369 --> 01:24:03,639
Jean, as long as I'm here,
I'll find you.

1495
01:24:05,341 --> 01:24:07,376
And then,
I'll drive by your house,

1496
01:24:07,410 --> 01:24:09,245
I'll go to the same places
you go,

1497
01:24:09,278 --> 01:24:11,514
I'll take all the risks.

1498
01:24:11,547 --> 01:24:13,582
You know how many times
I've driven by your house

1499
01:24:13,616 --> 01:24:15,751
just in the hope
of seeing you?

1500
01:24:18,754 --> 01:24:21,390
It's the only answer.

1501
01:24:21,424 --> 01:24:24,827
And after we've been away
from each other for a while,

1502
01:24:26,362 --> 01:24:28,664
our lives will go on.

1503
01:24:28,697 --> 01:24:32,435
Maybe not right away,
but in time.

1504
01:24:36,472 --> 01:24:37,740
I can't stay.

1505
01:24:39,208 --> 01:24:42,245
You're a much stronger person
than I am

1506
01:24:42,278 --> 01:24:44,147
and I just don't trust myself
that much.

1507
01:24:47,316 --> 01:24:50,353
Sometimes when you
don't know what else to do...

1508
01:24:52,388 --> 01:24:53,522
You run.

1509
01:25:04,400 --> 01:25:06,202
Your hair is turning
a little gray.

1510
01:25:07,403 --> 01:25:09,205
Mine, too.

1511
01:25:09,238 --> 01:25:10,806
Nobody will ever see mine,
I'm too vain.

1512
01:25:14,443 --> 01:25:16,745
I'll wonder what
you will look like
in years to come.

1513
01:25:18,514 --> 01:25:20,449
You'll probably
turn all silver.

1514
01:25:23,519 --> 01:25:25,888
Never felt for anyone
the way I feel
about you, Jean.

1515
01:25:28,524 --> 01:25:29,592
You have.

1516
01:25:29,625 --> 01:25:30,826
You've forgotten.

1517
01:25:31,727 --> 01:25:33,629
You felt it with Carol.

1518
01:25:33,662 --> 01:25:35,264
I felt it with Roger.

